<FIRST>r a PM-GraniteScrapped     01-07 0187</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Granite Scrapped,0192</SECOND>
<HEAD>South African Granite Scrapped For Bus Tunnel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city's transit and sewage authority is giving
up $480,000 of granite it bought for a downtown bus tunnel because
the stone came from South Africa, the agency announced.
   ``It would violate the spirit of our policy and would be an
affront to the community'' to use the granite, executive Alan Gibbs
told the Metro Council Thursday.
   The granite _ enough to cover 24,000 square feet _ is sitting in
supply yards in Italy, where it was cut.
   ``We're going to have to eat the cost,'' said David Kalberer,
superintendent of the $430 million tunnel project. Metro hopes to
sell the granite for scrap to recoup some of the cost, he added.
   Seattle Mayor Charles Royer agreed with the decision.
   ``This could be a serious affront and embarrassment for lots of
people,'' he said.
   The Metro Council banned the purchase of South African goods
because of that country's policy of racial segregation, or
apartheid, after a county councilman and city councilman protested
the use of South African steel in tunnel work in 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
