<FIRST>r a PM-Names     01-07 0977</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Names,1017</SECOND>
<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rock star Prince has made a clean breast of it
in the new year by getting a new manager, lawyer and accountant.
   Prince has hired film director Albert Magnoli as his manager,
replacing the management team of Bob Cavallo, Joe Ruffalo and Steve
Fargnoli, said Alan Leeds, operations manager for PRN Productions
Inc. Magnoli directed Prince's 1984 hit movie ``Purple Rain.''
   ``It's a new year,'' Leeds said Friday, explaining the change
which took effect Tuesday. He declined to elaborate.
   Prince also severed his 11-year relationship with attorney Lee
Phillips and retained the Los Angeles law firm of Ziffren,
Brittenham and Branca, Leeds said. He also replaced Moultrie
Accountancy with the accounting firm of Breslauer, Jacobson, Rutman
and Sherman of Los Angeles.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Broadway debut of the hit British comedy
``Lettice &amp; Lovage'' has been postponed until next season because
its star, Maggie Smith, is still recovering from a fractured
shoulder, a spokeswoman for the play said.
   The play, which won the London Evening Standard award for best
comedy of 1988, had been scheduled to open on Broadway April 2 but
now will be pushed back to the 1989-90 season, spokeswoman Merle
Frimark said Friday. She gave no specific dates.
   Miss Smith broke her shoulder while riding a bicycle on vacation
in November.
   The play, written by Peter Shaffer, author of ``Amadeus'' and
``Equus,'' concerns an eccentric woman who gives tours through the
stately homes of England.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grand Ole Opry star Johnny Russell, who
suffered a mild heart attack earlier this week, is to undergo heart
bypass surgery, according to his publicist.
   ``He will be transferred to St. Thomas Hospital on Monday and
then the surgery is tentatively scheduled for Tuesday morning,''
publicist Steve Campbell said Friday.
   Russell, 48, who wrote the song ``Act Naturally,'' was in stable
condition after being admitted to Nashville Memorial Hospital on
Tuesday after complaining of chest pains.
   ``He's eating well and in good spirits. He even joked about it,
saying when he gets out of the hospital, he could join Waylon
(Jennings) and (Johnny) Cash as a trio to perform a song called
``Bypass 101.''
   Both country music singers had bypasses in the last month.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farms, estates and mansions belonging to
notables such as country music singers Ronnie Milsap and Hank
Williams Sr. will be auctioned Jan. 21 for up to $30 million, an
auctioneer said.
   Among the properties being sold are the Giles County Milky Way
Farms retreat built by candy bar magnate Frank C. Mars, the farm of
Milsap and the former Nashville estate of Williams.
   Auctioneer Linda Arvin Hensley says the sale of 200 properties
will be ``the largest diversified auction ever in Tennessee
history.''
   ``It is not a distress sale,'' said Hensley, who has spent the
last several months organizing the properties and a catalog
distributed to thousands of potential bidders across the country.
   ``We are auctioning off history and we are auctioning the
future,'' she said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: A version is moving on sports wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dave Winfield is suing his boss, George
Steinbrenner, for more than $1 million that the star outfielder
claims the New York Yankees owner owes to his foundation for
fighting drug abuse.
   In a lawsuit filed Friday in U.S. District Court, Winfield
charged that Steinbrenner has not complied with a stipulation of his
contract to pay $300,000 a year to the David M. Winfield Foundation.
   Steinbrenner, in a statement, said an investigation of the
foundation discovered ``numerous questionable practices'' that would
be outlined in a counter-suit to be filed Monday.
   ``I just wish he had chosen another course, but there can be no
turning back now,'' said Steinbrenner, who has been publicly feuding
with Winfield for several years.
   Kenneth E. Warner, Steinbrenner's attorney, said the Yankees'
suit will allege excessive limousine expenses of more than $40,000
over a two-year period, excessive and disproportionate management
and administrative costs and other items.
   Winfield's suit seeks $450,000 that he says Steinbrenner owes
going back to Sept. 1, 1987, plus the balance owed for the duration
of the player's 10-year contract, for a total of $1,050,000.
   A Winfield Foundation statement said it was the third time the
foundation has had to sue Steinbrenner for non-compliance. In 1982
and 1983, Steinbrenner paid the full amount owed, it said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steve Wozniak, co-founder of Apple
Computer Inc., has briefly set aside his floppy disks to spin record
discs.
   The 33-year-old entrepreneur this week made his third appearance
on San Jose-based KSJO-FM, acting as substitute co-host of a morning
drive-time program, said station manager David Baronfeld.
   ``Our audience is between 22 and 38,'' said Baronfeld. ``He
reaches that upper end. They can react to a guy like Steve who grew
up listening to Santana and the Doobie Brothers.''
   Wozniak is an avid collector of vintage rock 'n' roll albums and
also organized two ``US Festivals,'' high-tech concert festivals
that married modern music with computer technology.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pauline Collins, who played the saucy maid Sarah
on the British television series ``Upstairs, Downstairs,'' will make
her Broadway debut in a one-woman comedy about a middle-aged English
housewife.
   ``Shirley Valentine,'' written by Willy Russell, author of the
play and film ``Educating Rita,'' concerns a housewife who dreams of
a life beyond the kitchen sink.
   The show, which was a success in London last winter, will open
Feb. 16 at the Booth Theater after a week of previews, said Philip
Rinaldi, a spokesman for the show.
   Collins will appear under a special exchange agreement between
American and British Actors' Equity associations that will allow
American Kathleen Rowe McAllen to appear in London this spring in
``Aspects of Love,'' a new Andrew Lloyd Webber musical.
</TEXT>
