<FIRST>r i PM-Ethiopia-Culture     01-07 0623</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ethiopia-Culture,0641</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeal for Funds to Rebuild Ancient Ethiopian Monomuents</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: First available for Saturday AMs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ABEBE ANDUALEM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GONDAR, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a modest tent surrounded by crumbling
palaces where Ethiopian emperors reigned for 250 years, a United
Nations official appealed for funds to rebuild the grandeur of this
Marxist state's feudal past.
   ``These sites are part of our universal cultural heritage,''
UNESCO chief Federico Mayor told Western ambassadors, international
donors and representatives of other U.N. agencies Thursday. ``The
history of this region is as imposing as the historical remains are
impressive.''
   The director-general of the United Nations Educational,
Scientific and Cultural Organization arrived in Ethiopia's capital
Wednesday to dramatize the need for $14.5 million for Ethiopia's
10-year program to restore palaces, monasteries, castles and other
monuments that UNESCO has declared heritages of mankind.
   Mayor immediately flew to Gondar, 285 miles northwest of Addis
Ababa, a city graced by palaces and castles built by emperors who
ruled between 1632 and 1868.
   Palaces such as Gondar's Ras Beit are in need of restoration
because they have been used continuously for two or more centuries.
Ras Beit is an 18th century edifice used as offices of President
Mengistu Haile Mariam's government.
   Some monuments were nearly destroyed in warfare between different
dynasties and in resistance to foreign invasions. Others fell into
disrepair because of neglect.
   In need of repair are the 11 fantastical churches hewn from rock
in northern Lalibella town, monasteries around Lake Tana, the source
of the Blue Nile, and the granite-carved obelisks of Axum which once
rose 13 storys high.
   Axum's tallest obelisk, an intricately carved stone column that
once stretched up 100 feet, has fallen. The tallest still standing
is more than 75 feet high, the height of a 10-story building.
   They were built when a a flourishing kingdom existed around 500
B.C. in Axum, 341 miles north of Addis Ababa in wartorn Tigray
province. The king and his subjects embraced Coptic Christianity in
330 A.D. During the Middle Ages this kingdom gave way, through
palace feuds and intrigues, to others in the south.
   However by 1636, Gondar had become the capital of centralized
authority in the mountainous region, giving Ethiopia a political
entity long before European colonization.
   Mayor said Ethiopia's monuments ``are treasures, a legacy of
civilizations spanning more than 40 centuries.
   ``Anyone who sees the state into which the masterworks have
fallen would shudder and move into action to preserve these and
other jewels of Ethiopia's past for the common enrichment of present
and future generations,'' he said.
   He appealed to the international community to contribute money,
equipment and services for the restoration.
   The 50-state Organization of African Unity announced from its
Addis Ababa headquarters the first donation of $10,000 to help
restore treasures of one of the continent's most ancient
civilizations.
   Ethiopian Culture Minister Ghirma Yilma said his country's rich
cultural history had attracted scholars from many parts of the
world. Ethiopian artifacts and art are to be found in museums all
over the world, he noted.
   Ghirma said the government, established after a 1974 coup ousted
the late Emperor Haile Selassie, was keen to see the ancient
monuments restored.
   Gondar, Lalibella and Axum form the Ethiopian Tourist
Orgnization's ``northern historic route.'' However, tourism there
has been handicapped since the rebel Tigrean Peoples' Liberation
Army took up arms against the government 14 years ago, demanding
more autonomy for the province.
   Mayor took issue with reporters who asked whether money spent on
restoration of ancient monuments could not be better spent on people
affected by natural calamities like the droughts and famines which
intermittently afflict the East African nation.
   ``Guaranteeing opportunities to learn about and share our common
heritage is also indispensable,'' he said.
</TEXT>
