<FIRST>r a PM-TowerHospitalized     01-07 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tower Hospitalized,0360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tower In Good Condition After Colon Surgery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUZANNE GAMBOA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The physician who operated on former Sen. John
Tower said the colon surgery shouldn't interfere with his serving as
secretary of defense in President-elect George Bush's cabinet.
   ``Sen. Tower is in excellent health and he should expect a 100
percent recovery,'' Dr. R.D Dignan said Friday. ``And I see no
reason whatsoever why he can't pick up where he left off.''
   Dignan and other doctors removed a polyp and a one-foot section
of Tower's colon during a three-hour operation Thursday. The polyp
and section of colon appear to be benign, doctors said, although
final reports from an analysis of the growth and tissue were not
expected to be available until today.
   There is little chance of previously detected malignant cells
resurfacing, Dignan added.
   Tower, 63, appointed defense secretary-designate by Bush on Dec.
16, was listed in good condition Friday night, hospital officials
said.
   The former Republican senator is expected to remain hospitalized
another seven or eight days, and Dignan has recommended that he rest
in Dallas another four or five days after being released.
   Doctors discovered the colon polyp Dec. 27 when physicians
performed a colonoscopy and removed a cancerous rectal polyp they
had discovered in November.
   ``All of the malignant cells from the rectal polyp have been
removed and there is nothing but a high likelihood that a cure has
been achieved. I think it would be the remotest possibility that he
would have any additional trouble,'' Dignan said.
   Dignan said the surgical procedure is standard for a broad-base
polyp and similar to surgery performed on President Reagan.
   Physicians also removed lymph nodes and a small portion of
Tower's small intestine.
   Tower must return for regular examinations to insure that other
polyps do not develop, but will not be expected to make any changes
in his diet or take any prescription medicine.
   Tower, who retired in 1985 after 24 years in the Senate, served
as an arms negotiator for President Reagan and headed the White
House's Iran-Contra investigative panel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
