<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,000</SECOND>
<HEAD>Citibank Wins Appeals Court Decision</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Citibank, the largest bank in the nation, can
operate a subsidiary to insure municipal bonds, says the U.S. Court
of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit.
   In a precedent-setting ruling, an appeals court panel said Friday
the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency, the chief regulator
of nationally chartered banks, properly permitted Citibank to
purchase the American Municipal Bond Assurance Corp., known as AMBAC.
   The American Insurance Association challenged the decision by
Comptroller Robert L. Clarke and lost in the U.S. District Court
here. The association won a decision by an appeals panel in August
but Friday's decision reverses that part of the ruling.
   Stephen Katsanos, a spokesman for the Federal Deposit Insurance
Corp., which insures bank deposits and is the primary regulator of
state-chartered banks that are not members of the Federal Reserve,
said FDIC Chairman L. William Seidman was ``quite pleased'' with the
decision.
</TEXT>
