<NOTE>---</NOTE>
<NOTE>Federal Government Wants Airlines to Replace Rivets on Older Boeing</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   727s.
   WASHINGTON (AP) _ The Federal Aviation Administration. wants
airlines to replace thousands of rivets on more than 600 older
Boeing 727s. The goverment also wants them to initiate inspection
procedures until the modifications can be completed.
   The FAA estimated Friday that the repairs and extra inspections
of 623 older Boeing 727s will cost the airlines approximately $35.7
million.
   The proposed directive on the Boeing 727s requires that airlines
over the next four years replace from 3,300 to 4,150 rivets,
depending on the model of 727 involved. It said the ``countersunk''
rivets now on the planes are believed to cause cracking under some
circumstances, while the substitute ``button-head'' is less likely
to do so.
   The proposed FAA directive is similar to an order issued last
October for older Boeing 737s. A final order will not be issued
until after a brief comment period.
