<FIRST>r i PM-Libya-UN     01-07 0687</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Libya-UN,0714</SECOND>
<HEAD>Washington, Libya In Verbal Dogfight Over Photos</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Libya, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and Libya engaged in a
verbal dogfight in the Security Council over the authenticity of
photos that Washington says prove a Libyan MiG was armed when it was
shot down by U.S. jets.
   The U.S. envoy said Friday the photographs clearly show a Libyan
aircraft armed with missiles, not _ as he put it _ ``a bouquet of
flowers.'' He said the U.S. pilots acted in self-defense after using
evasive air maneuvers five times to try to avoid the approaching
jets.
   The Libyan envoy called the photographs ``fakes ... fabricated
pictures ... directed in a Hollywood manner'' by actors and clever
editors. Libya says the planes were unarmed reconnaissance craft.
   The already bad relations between the United States and Libya
worsened in recent weeks with U.S. assertions that Col. Moammar
Gadhafi's government is ready to begin production of chemical
weapons in a desert factory outside Tripoli. Libya says the plant is
designed to make pharmaceuticals.
   Washington's U.N. Ambassador Vernon A. Walters dramatically
exhibited two blurred photographs Friday that he said showed
missiles under the wings and fuselage of one of the two Soviet-built
MiG-23s shot down by two U.S. F-14 Tomcats on Wednesday over
international waters of the Mediterranean Sea.
   U.S. officials say they believe the other plane was similarly
armed.
   The photographs were passed around the council during the
session, which Libya had sought in order to condemn the United
States. The session adjourned until Monday morning.
   The United States and its British ally are expected to veto the
resolution of condemnation drafted by the 101-nation Non-Aligned
Movement.
   About 25 speakers, mostly from Arab and non-aligned nations, have
denounced the U.S. action in the U.N. session. No one has supported
it, but U.S. allies have not yet spoken.
   Libya says the U.S. government wants to provoke a Libyan
retaliation so it can launch a full-scale attack.
   U.S. planes raided two Libyan cities in 1986 to retaliate for
purported Libyan support of terrorism in connection with the bombing
of a West German disco frequented by U.S. servicemen.
   A spokesman for Libyan Information Minister Rajab Abou Dabbous
said Friday that 14 U.S. planes _ not two _ attacked the Libyan
craft.
   The United States says the photographs were taken from videotape
of the encounter made by the pilot of one of the U.S. aircraft. It
says they show two views of a single aircraft armed with Aphid and
Apex missiles.
   However, not everyone was convinced on Friday. Soviet Ambassador
Alexander M. Belonogov told the council that the U.S. military
action was ``absolutely unfounded.''
   He said the photographs were blurred and added, ``It's immaterial
whether the Libyan planes carried any missiles or were just pure
reconnaissance planes. ... We cannot recognize the right of a
military plane of one country to shoot down a military aircraft of
another country just because they both happen to be very close to
each other in international airspace.''
   ``I'm not going to get into a hassle over the quality of image,''
Walters retorted after Libya criticized his evidence. ``The
important thing is that U.S. aircraft made five evasive maneuvers to
turn away from the oncoming MiGs.
   ``If you are walking down a dark alley at night and you see a man
who has a gun, and you cross the street and he crosses the street,
you slow down and he slows down, you speed up and he speeds up,
you've got to realize that he's not coming to present you with a
bouquet of flowers,'' said Walters.
   He said the U.S. planes were on a routine mission and acted in
self-defense.
   However, the Libyan envoy reminded the 15-member council that in
July a U.S. warship shot down an Iranian commercial airliner in the
Persian Gulf because crewmen mistakenly believed it to be an
attacking warplane. All 290 people on the plane were killed.
   ``We are in the country of Hollywood,'' he told reporters. ``It
is very well edited, very well done _ and it is not true.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
