<FIRST>r a PM-HijackerSentenced     01-07 0289</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hijacker Sentenced,0295</SECOND>
<HEAD>Skyjacker Who Spent 5 Years In Cuban Prison Gets 5 More In U.S. Prison</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who hijacked a jetliner to
Cuba and spent five years in prison there has been sentenced to
spend another five years in a U.S. prison.
   Robert Richter, 31, of suburban Chicago, received the sentence
Friday from U.S. District Judge William Zloch, who rejected a
federal probation officer's recommendation to let Richter remain
free on probation.
   Richter hijacked an Air Florida flight from Fort Lauderdale on
July 7, 1983, when he was 26 years old and reportedly fascinated
with Cuba.
   Less than 24 hours earlier, the U.S. government said it had
received word that Cuba was cracking down on hijackers and that any
sky pirates landing there could expect to spend 50 years in a Cuban
prison.
   When Richter returned to the United States in June, he pleaded
innocent to U.S. charges. He later changed his plea.
   Richter's odyssey began when he boarded Air Florida Flight 8 at
Fort Lauderdale-Hollywood International Airport. He used a fake bomb
to force the crew to take the Boeing 737 to Havana instead of Tampa,
its scheduled destination. Air Florida is now defunct.
   Richter was arrested, tried, convicted and sentenced to 20 years
in prison. He probably would still be in the prison in Cuba if not
for the efforts of his father, Chicago businessman John Richter.
   Neither Richter's father nor the FBI have discussed how Richter's
release was achieved. But the FBI has insisted that the U.S.
government was not involved in the negotiations.
   Since his return from Cuba, Richter has been free on a $250,000
bond signed by his father, and has worked for his father's business.
</TEXT>
