<DOCNO> AP890107-0041 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-07-89 0445EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Lite     01-07 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lite,0480</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>McCOOK, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A book containing H.G. Wells' ``The Time
Machine'' has been returned to the McCook Public Library, and none
too soon. It was due 18 years ago.
   The paperback book, which also included Wells' ``War of the
Worlds,'' was returned along with a letter via mail by Ronald L.
Sklaver of Los Angeles, who found it at a bargain bookstore in Rome,
said librarian Melba Herrmann.
   ``It is now your turn to sell it on a bargain shelf,'' he wrote.
``It's too bad that Wells' time machine didn't work or we could know
how the overdue book ended up in Rome on a bargain shelf.''
   Sklaver's letter said he came across the book at an English
language bookstore. He said it took him two months to read it and
then he decided to return it.
   On the library's fine schedule of 5 cents per day for overdue
books, the 6,716-day period would have come to $335.80. However, the
maximum fine is $5 so whoever checked the book out in 1970 need not
worry.
   The librarian said there are no records of who borrowed the book.
   The library paid 95 for the book, Ms. Herrmann said.
   Ms. Herrmann said she planned to write Sklaver a letter of thanks.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The proud father of newborn quintuplets says he's
taking it in stride and is ready to man the diaper brigade.
   ``It's one of those cases where whatever happens, you make the
best of it,'' Billy Wilson, 34, of Auburn Hills, said Friday at a
press conference.
   The quints, nine weeks premature, were born by Caesarean section
over a period of two minutes starting a 6:37 p.m. Thursday to Mary
Jo Wilson, 30.
   Cameron Patrick, Anthony Michael, Shelby Nicole, Rebecca Irene,
and Elizabeth Ashley ranged in weight at birth from 2 pounds, 9
ounces to 3 pounds, 7 ounces.
   All five and their 30-year-old mother were listed in stable
condition, doctors at Sinai Hospital said.
   A beaming Wilson, wearing all five of the babies' identification
bracelets on his wrist, said while he may not be prepared for
rearing five babies at once, he has some experience.
   ``I changed more diapers on Brad than Mary did,'' the diesel
mechanic for General Motors Corp. said of the couple's 2{-year-old
son.
   The incidence of quintuplets is one in 65.6 million without the
use of fertility drugs, according to a hospital fact sheet.
Estimates on the chances of multiple births range from 6 percent to
30 percent when fertility drugs are used, as in the Wilsons' case,
Schwartz said.
   Mrs. Wilson is handling the ordeal well, nurse Lisa Hahn said.
   ``She has a very good sense of humor,'' Hahn said. ``Basically,
she has to.''
</TEXT>
