<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--HaitiansIntercepted     01-07 0153</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Haitians Intercepted,0155</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coast Guard Finds 94 Haitians On Stranded Boat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most of the 94 Haitians intercepted by the U.S.
Coast Guard on a 30-foot wooden sailboat off the Florida Keys have
been detained until a judge decides whether they should be deported,
authorities said.
   The Haitians, who told officials they had spent 15 days on the
boat, were rescued Friday after it ran onto rocks off the coast of
Grassy Key near Marathon, the Coast Guard said.
   ``This is the largest number of Haitians to get here in nine
years,'' said Perry Rivkind, district director of the Immigration
and Naturalization Service in Miami.
   Three of the refugees were treated at Fishermen's Hospital in
Marathon. One woman had gone into labor, one man had suffered a
possible heart attack and another man had fainted, Rivkind said.
   Rivkind said there were ten pregnant women and three children in
the group.
