<FILEID>AP-NR-01-07-89 0544EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon     01-07 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Killed In New Shiite Clashes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Feuding Shiite Moslem militias battled
with mortars and machine guns in Beirut's violence-scarred streets
and the hills of south Lebanon today despite a call by Iran's
president to end the weeklong fighting.
   Four people were killed and 12 wounded in battles between the
Syrian-backed Amal militia and the pro-Iranian Hezbollah, police
said.
   Syrian troops intervened in Moslem west Beirut to impose a
precarious cease-fire in the capital.
   A police spokesman said three combatants were killed and eight
wounded in the fierce street battles that spilled into the battered
commercial district of Moslem west Beirut.
   The spokesman, who cannot be named under standing regulations,
said a Hezbollah fighter was killed and four people wounded in
artillery and mortar exchanges in south Lebanon.
   By police count, 33 people have been killed and 92 wounded since
the Shiite clashes flared Dec. 31.
   Hundreds of people have been killed or wounded in nine months of
intermittent fighting between the two factions, who are battling for
dominance of Lebanon's 1 million Shiites, the country's largest sect.
   President Ali Khamenei of Iran appealed Friday to both factions
to end the bloodshed.
   ``Vengeance will not solve anything in Lebanon,'' Iran's official
Islamic Republic News Agency quoted Khamenei as saying in Tehran.
The dispatch was monitored in Cyprus.
   The thud of exploding shells and the crackle of automatic weapons
fire echoed across Beirut during the night as Amal militiamen staged
hit-and-run attacks against Hezbollah positions near the western
edge of the Green Line that divides Beirut into Moslem and Christian
sectors.
   Hezbollah responded by firing mortars into Amal-controlled
districts of west Beirut to ease the pressure on its fighters, the
police spokesman said.
   Syrian troops armed with AK-47 assault rifles and
rocket-propelled grenades moved into the contested sector before
dawn to enforce a cease-fire, he reported.
   The clashes were the heaviest fighting between the Shiite
factions in west Beirut since Nov. 27, when the Syrians imposed a
cease-fire after six days of violence in which 40 people were killed
and 87 wounded.
   In south Lebanon, Amal gunners fired howitzers at Hezbollah
fighters in the villages of Jbaa, Jarjou, Arab Saleem, Louwaizeh and
Ein Bouswar on the northwestern edge of Israel's self-proclaimed
``security zone,'' which runs along Lebanon's southern border.
   Hezbollah fired mortars into Amal supply lines.
   ``No change of positions was reported in the region,'' the police
spokesman said, who noted that the southern fighting died down early
today.
   Hezbollah, or Party of God, is made up of Shiite fundamentalists
loyal to Iran's Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini. The more secular Amal,
Syria's main surrogate in Lebanon, rejects Iran's religious
influence over Lebanon's Shiites.
</TEXT>
