<FILEID>AP-NR-01-07-89 0550EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-India-Afghan     01-07 0548</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India-Afghan,0565</SECOND>
<HEAD>Afghan Official: King Can Play Role But Najib Won't Quit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior member of Afghanistan's
Soviet-style ruling party said today that deposed King Zahir Shah
could play a role in ending the Afghan war but President Najib would
not resign.
   Najmuddin Kawyani, one of 14 Politburo members of the People's
Democratic Party of Afghanistan, accused anti-government guerrillas
of blocking efforts to form a broad-based government.
   Leaders of the Afghan Moslem resistance, who have been meeting
this week in Pakistan with the Soviet first deputy foreign minister,
Yuli Vorontsov, vehemently reject the participation of Najib and his
party in any future government.
   ``Najib will not resign, and we have not heard any such thing
from Moscow,'' Kawyani told a news conference at the Afghan Embassy
in New Delhi.
   Najib told Western journalists in Kabul last month he was willing
to do anything to bring peace to his country as Soviet forces
withdraw, but he avoided saying whether that included resigning.
   Kawyani, who comes from Najib's own Parchami faction of the
party, said: ``I must emphasize that without the participation of
the People's Democratic Party of Afghanistan, peace is impossible.''
   Asked about Zahir Shah, the deposed monarch whom Vorontsov met in
Italy last month, Kawyani said:
   ``The People's Democratic Party of Afghanistan is of the view
that the ex-king, Zahir Shah, can play a role in a political
settlement of Afghanistan. ... We're waiting for him to express a
point of view. We're interested in a settlement. The return of Zahir
Shah does not mean a return of the monarchy.''
   Zahir Shah was overthrown in 1973 by his cousin, Mohammad Daoud,
who was killed five years later in the coup that installed the
Soviet-backed government. In 1979, Soviet troops intervened in
Afghanistan to help defend the government from Moslem guerrilla
attacks.
   In the last few years, the party has sought to distance itself
publicly from its Marxist beginnings, but the Moslem resistance
movement, composed of seven Pakistan-based parties and eight
Iran-based parties, routinely refers to the party as ``godless
communists.''
   Zahir Shah is increasingly mentioned as the only Afghan leader
with sufficient stature to serve as even a symbolic leader.
   Vorontsov met resistance leaders in Saudi Arabia on Dec. 3,
giving the guerrillas the Kremlin's first public recognition as a
negotiating force for Afghanistan's future.
   The guerrillas have been fighting Kabul's government since the
1978 coup. With arms supplied by the United States, Pakistan, China
and several Arab nations, the guerrillas also attacked Soviet forces
that numbered 115,000 a year ago.
   The Soviets started withdrawing troops last May under a
U.N.-sponsored accord signed in Geneva. The remaining 50,000 Red
Army soldiers are scheduled to leave Afghanistan by Feb. 15 under
the accord.
   Kawyani, in his late 30s with a black mustache reminiscent of
Josef Stalin, accused the United States and Pakistan of violating
the Geneva Accord by continuing to arm the guerrillas.
   He demanded Pakistan stop providing shelter for the guerrillas.
The seven mujahedeen parties based in Pakistan openly maintain
offices in Peshawar, 20 miles from the Afghan border.
   ``A council of peace should be formed from all the involved
parties,'' Kawyani said. ``Another option is an international
conference under the auspices of the United Nations.''
</TEXT>
