<FIRST>r i PM-Mexico-Trotsky     01-07 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mexico-Trotsky,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trotsky Son Returns From First Soviet Visit in 51 Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The grandson of Soviet revolutionary leader
Leon Trotsky, back from his first visit to the Soviet Union in a
half-century, said the Soviet attitude toward his grandfather is
full of contradictions.
   However, Esteban Volkow Bronstein said the fact that he was
granted a visa indicated a slight improvement in his grandfather's
status.
   Volkow said Friday that he spent five days in Moscow last month
visiting Alexandra Zakharonavna, his half-sister and Trotsky's
granddaughter.
   ``She's very gravely ill with cancer,'' said Volkow.
Nevertheless, he said, they had a happy reunion. Volkow said he
hadn`t seen his sister since he fled the Soviet Union with his
mother in 1931, when he was 5 years old.
   Volkow was living with Trotsky in Mexico City when the former
head of the Red Army was assassinated on Josef Stalin's orders on
Aug. 20, 1940.
   Trotsky, born Lev Davidovich Bronstein, was one of the leaders of
the October 1917 revolution that established the Soviet Union, but
he lost a power struggle with Stalin and was exiled in 1929.
   Under Stalinism, Trotsky was deemed a non-person, reviled in the
Soviet Union.
   It was only recently that Trotsky's reputation began to be
revived as Mikhail Gorbachev's policy of glasnost gathered steam.
   Trotsky's name is now sometimes mentioned in public and he is
described as an enemy of Stalin rather than an enemy of socialism
and the revolution.
   Last year, the Soviet Supreme Court rehabilitated a son, Volkow's
uncle Sergei Sedov, who was executed on Stalin's orders in 1937. The
court ordered all charges against Sedov dropped.
   Volkow said he traveled to Moscow shortly after the earthquake
last month that devastated Armenia, killing about 55,000 people.
   ``We had trouble getting seats, there were so many people flying
to Moscow to help,'' said Volkow.
   He said in addition to visiting his sister, he met with about 500
members of a group formed in Trotksy's memory. He said he was also
interviewed on videotape by Ogonyonk, the magazine on the leading
edge of glasnost.
   ``I don't know if they'll broadcast the videotape,'' he said. ``I
think it was for use sometime in the future.''
   Volkow, a retired chemical engineer, believes his grandfather's
role in the founding of the Soviet Union should not be distorted or
hidden.
   Volkow also said he left the Soviet Union at such a young age
that he remembers almost nothing. He now considers himself a Mexican
and said Moscow was extremely cold.
   ``It was all snow,'' Volkow said.
</TEXT>
