<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Rites     01-07 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Rites,0394</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan Plans 29 Funeral Rites For Hirohito</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Obit-Hirohito, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANICE FUHRMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan will bury Emperor Hirohito after weeks of
ceremonies that will follow closely the rituals and pageantry of his
father's funeral 62 years ago.
   The formal state funeral is planned for Feb. 24, Kyodo news
service reported, quoting government sources. There was no immediate
government announcement.
   Hirohito died today from intestinal cancer. He was 87.
   Ceremonies to purify the mausoleum where Hirohito's body will
lay, to enshrine his spirit and to mark the departure of the
imperial hearse from the palace for the burial site are among 29
funeral rites planned.
   Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita will head a committee to decide
funeral details.
   Hirohito's father, Emperor Taisho, was buried 45 days after his
death on Dec. 25, 1926, in an elaborate garden ceremony that
included a funeral march of 6,000 people.
   ``Although there have been many changes since then, including
major changes in the constitution, in practical terms there won't be
many alterations in the funeral rites,'' a palace official said
before Hirohito's death.
   That would mean there could be more than 61 different ceremonies,
rites and imperial court appearances extending over at least two
years before his son Akihito's formal ascension to Japan's
2,600-year-old Chrysanthemum Throne.
   Many are directly linked to Japan's native Shinto religion, for
which the emperor serves as chief priest.
   Hirohito was considered a living Shinto god until allied
occupation authorities forced him to renounce his divinity after
World War II. The postwar constitution makes the emperor the
``symbol of state.''
   Officials say Hirohito's body will be placed in a casket two or
three days after his death.
   The funeral, on a day that will be declared a national holiday,
will include a procession of top officials and foreign dignitaries
to a royal burial ground.
   In a departure from common Japanese practice, palace officials
said the emperor will not be cremated.
   Government officials avoided talking about the funeral before
Hirohito's death, believing it inappropriate while he was still
battling his illness.
   The 45-day period after Taisho's death was likely related to the
time required for foreign dignitaries to travel to Japan, since only
boat transportation was available at the time, the palace official
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
