<DOCNO> AP890107-0054 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-07-89 0715EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Hirohito-USReax     01-07 0566</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hirohito-US Reax,0583</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese-Americans Mourn Death of An Emperor</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hirohito</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   In Hawaii, where one-quarter of the population is of Japanese
descent, Emperor Hirohito was remembered as a symbol of unity who
helped Japan emerge as a leading democracy in Asia.
   Hirohito, who reigned for 62 years, died today of intestinal
cancer at age 87. His eldest son, Crown Prince Akihito, 55,
immediately became the 125th occupant of the Chrysanthemum Throne.
   Elsewhere Friday, Americans made books of condolence in
Washington state and Colorado as officials planned to mark his
passing in ceremonies during the coming days.
   In Washington, D.C., President Reagan offered condolences and
lauded Hirohito for playing ``a truly heroic role'' in urging his
country to surrender after the atomic bombing of Japan by the United
States at the close of World War II.
   Mourning was most evident at the Japanese consulate in Honolulu,
where Hirohito had planted a tree during a 1975 visit to the
Islands. The Japanese flag flew at half-staff and officials
monitored Japanese radio accounts of Hirohito's death.
   Consul General Tadayuki Nonoyama invited mourners to the
consulate on Monday and Tuesday to sign a book of condolences for
the royal family.
   Nonoyama said his own loss was made greater because he had known
Hirohito, once serving as an interpreter in the royal household.
   ``I have a deep affection for the emperor. He was a very sincere
man,'' Nonoyama said.
   Sen. Spark Matsunaga, D-Hawaii, said he had great respect for
Hirohito, with whom he met on several occasions.
   ``The emperor's role as a symbol of unity contributed to the
miracle performed by the Japanese people in developing their country
as the leading democratic nation in post-war Asia, politically,
economically and culturally,'' Matsunaga said.
   Honolulu Mayor Frank Fasi said Hirohito ``will long be remembered
as the god who became a man, and through his personal humility
brought respect and dignity out of the tragedy of war.''
   In Seattle, plans to mark Hirohito's passing would be formalized
next week, said Christine Rose, assistant director of the Japan
America Society of the State of Washington. Seattle's Japanese
consulate also would have a book of condolences for signing, she
said.
   In California, Japanese-Americans voiced restrained sympathy over
the monarch's passing.
   ``I suspect that in a way the Japanese-Americans who are living
in the U.S. may take the death a little more seriously, or hard,''
said Peter Duus, professor of modern Japanese history at Stanford
University.
   ``When the older generation left Japan the emperor was almost
like a Russian Czar, surrounded by religious awe. And the younger
generation here, as a result, have a wonderful time-capsule picture
of the Japan their parents knew,'' Duus added.
   Leon Kimura, president of the Japanese-American Citizens League's
San Jose chapter, said, ``This is a shock even though we knew he was
sick.''
   ``Even though we are Japanese-Americans there is still some
strong feelings for our homeland,'' Kimura said.
   In Colorado, Japanese residents planned a ceremony Monday to
memorialize the emperor, but the state's Buddhist community planned
no commemoration to avoid misunderstanding over Hirohito's wartime
role.
   Joe Ozaki, vice president of the Japanese Association of
Colorado, said the organization made arrangements for a ``kicho,''
or memorial ceremony for the state's 7,000 Japanese to bow before a
portrait of the emperor and sign a condolence book on Monday at
Sakura Square, a Japanese commercial area in downtown Denver.
</TEXT>
