<FIRST>r a PM-HungryBurglar     01-07 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hungry Burglar,0295</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fingerprint On Salad Dressing Jar Convicts 320-Pound Burglar</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHESAPEAKE, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 320-pound man whose appetite got the
best of him while he was burglarizing a home fixed himself a meal _
and one to go _ but was caught when authorities found his
fingerprint on a salad-dressing jar.
   ``This man is no overweight Goldilocks sampling their porridge
... He's a brazen thief,'' Deputy Commonwealth's Attorney Stephen
Givando-Cline said Friday at the trial of Darryl J. White.
   ``We have a man apparently overcome by the vigor of his own
appetite who stops during the course of his own burglary and
prepares himself a feast,'' Givando-Cline said.
   White, 24, of Chesapeake, was convicted of burglary, fined $1,000
and sentenced to 5{ years in prison.
   Givando-Cline said White, who is 6-foot-2, entered a townhouse
through an unlocked door on the night of June 4, 1986, while the
family of four slept upstairs. The prosecutor said White took a
videocassette recorder, tapes and $69.
   But White didn't leave after getting the loot, opting instead to
plunder the pantry, Givando-Cline said. Littering the counters were
a plate that previously held four salmon cutlets, an open loaf of
bread, orange peels and pitchers of milk, water and Kool-Aid.
   The burglar also packed a snack to go of luncheon meats, cheese,
oranges, ice cream and Kool-Aid, the prosecutor said.
   Givando-Cline said White's fingerprint was found on a jar of
Miracle Whip Light salad dressing in the kitchen.
   Randall D. Smith, White's court-appointed attorney, argued that
fingerprint evidence is not steadfast.
   ``For 20 years fingerprints can stay there,'' Smith said. ``Think
about that the next time you're in a grocery store and touch a jar
of mayonnaise there.''
</TEXT>
