<SECOND>PM-Philippines-Hostages, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0458,0469</SECOND>
<HEAD>Troops Retake Garrison In Philippines</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with 17 dead, troops recapturing
garrison, other details. Pickup 5th graf pvs, ``The policemen...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN GUERRERO ^Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ZAMBOANGA CITY, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Troops backed by helicopter
gunships today stormed a military garrison held by Moslem gunmen and
ended a three-day standoff in which at least 17 people were reported
killed.
   Gen. Renato de Villa, military chief of staff, said the camp _
captured Thursday by eight Moslem policemen and seven supporters who
took two high-ranking officers hostage _ was secured late this
afternoon.
   De Villa said eight soldiers and two civilians were wounded.
   He said 16 bodies, many burned beyond recognition, were found in
the headquarters building and the camp mosque. One of the rebel
supporters was killed and his wife was wounded in Thursday's
takeover.
   The military attacked the Moslems on Friday after the captives _
Brig. Gen. Eduardo Batalla and Col. Romeo Abendan _ were reported
killed. After that attack was repulsed, the military tried again
today.
   The military confirmed that Batalla was killed during the
standoff and said one of the 16 bodies recovered was tentatively
identified as Abendan.
   The policemen had been ordered to surrender to Batalla, the
regional Philippine Constabulary commander, to face murder charges
in a 1984 incident.
   The military said up to 60 other Moslems, including many
soldiers, had joined the rebel group after ransacking the garrison
armory.
   In Manila, President Corazon Aquino said she was ``grieved'' by
the loss of lives but added: ``Let there be no doubt about our
equally strong resolve to protect our people from such brutal and
senseless acts of violence.''
   At midmorning, two military UH-1 helicopters strafed the main
stronghold with machine gun fire and a Sikorsky helicopter fired
four rockets, setting the building on fire.
   Government troops surrounding the compound cheered as the
helicopters opened fire. The compound is in Zamboanga, 560 miles
south of Manila.
   The leader of the gunmen, patrolman Rizah Alih, was charged but
acquitted in the November 1984 slaying of Mayor Cesar Climaco. Three
weeks after Climaco's death, seven people were killed in a marine
raid on Alih's home.
   Alih faces murder charges in those deaths. Last month, Batalla
received permission to arrest Alih. Batalla ordered Alih and eight
others detained. All of them could be charged with murder or
conspiracy to commit murder.
   In an apparently unrelated incident, military sources said seven
marines were killed and two wounded today during an attack by Moslem
rebels on Basilan island, about 10 miles to the south.
   A military report said two rebels were also slain.
   About 5 million Moslems live in the Philippines, which has
population of 59 million.
</TEXT>
