<FIRST>r a PM-HudsonSuit 1stLd-Writethru a0469 01-07 0633</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hudson Suit, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0469,0647</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rock Hudson's Lover Sues Estate, Saying He Was Not Told About AIDS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT date of Hudson's death to October sted
July 1985. Note contents.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorneys representing the estate of Rock
Hudson portrayed a companion of the actor who died of AIDS as an
opportunist who threatened to go public with the love letters Hudson
had written him.
   But a lawyer for Marc Christian said his client was victimized by
the actor who died in October 1985 because Hudson concealed
knowledge of his incurable and contagious disease.
   Hudson's secretary, Mark Miller, hid Hudson's disease from
Christian until the whole world heard about it, attorney Harold
Rhoden told jurors Friday in Christian's $11 million lawsuit.
   ``Marc Christian got a call from Mark Miller in France,'' said
Rhoden. ``He said, `I'm sorry. The movie star told me not to tell
you, I know it's not fair. But I was only following orders.'''
   Rhoden said the trial would focus on whether Hudson had a duty to
warn his sexual partner that he had AIDS and whether Christian
should be compensated for emotional distress and the ``enhanced
fear'' that he, too, had been infected.
   The estate's attorney, Robert Mills, said Christian has not
developed AIDS, which supports his theory that the affair ended
shortly after it began.
   ``If he doesn't have AIDS what motivation is there for suing?''
he asked. ``And if it wasn't a movie star of Rock Hudson's stature
would he be suing?''
   Miller's lawyer, Andrew Banks, said Miller had vowed to keep
Hudson's illness secret from everyone, including Christian.
   ``This was a man Rock Hudson trusted closer than he would trust a
brother,'' he said. ``When Rock Hudson learned he had AIDS, he
turned to this friend he trusted with this terrible secret because
it would be safe.''
   But he said Miller did not believe that Hudson was continuing to
have sex with Christian.
   ``Rock Hudson told Mark Miller they were not having sex, that
they hadn't had sex since February 1984,'' Banks said.
   He also quoted Hudson as telling Miller: ``Give the kid what he
wants. He has letters.''
   Banks said Christian lived off Hudson as he lived off a woman 33
years his senior with whom he had an affair.
   ``What the evidence is going to show,'' said Banks, ``is he
(Christian) is interested in the will, money and publicity.
   ``When the Rock Hudson gravy train ended and Mr. Hudson died,
Marc Christian filed this suit because the will had been probated
and he wasn't in it,'' he said.
   Attorneys for Miller and the Hudson estate contend the love
affair between Hudson and Christian soured in early 1984 because
Christian told Hudson he had sold sex for money. They said Hudson
stopped having sex with Christian and allowed him to stay in his
home for the next 18 months only because Christian threatened to
expose the star's homosexuality.
   Rhoden said Hudson deluded his lover by hiding his disease and
was protected by Miller, who told Christian that Hudson had
anorexia, not AIDS.
   Rhoden described a tender 2{-year love affair that began when
Hudson and Christian met at a political fund-raiser in October 1982.
Christian was 28, and Hudson, 56.
   In early 1983, ``Hudson said he was falling in love with
Christian and that he hadn't felt this way since he was in high
school,'' Rhoden said.
   The men engaged in sex three to five times a week with neither
man using a condom, Rhoden said. Hudson developed symptoms of AIDS a
year later, including rashes and sores, profuse sweating and rapid
weight loss.
   Hudson was diagnosed with AIDS in June 1984, but decided not to
tell Christian, Rhoden said.
</TEXT>
