<FILEID>AP-NR-01-07-89 0829EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Azerbaijan     01-07 0381</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Azerbaijan,0394</SECOND>
<HEAD>Azerbaijani Refugee Count Reaches 160,000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of Azerbaijanis who fled neighboring
Armenia to their homeland in the face of ethnic unrest and a
devastating earthquake has swelled to 160,000, an Azerbaijani
official said today.
   Thousands of the refugees are camping in schools, clubs and other
public buildings as they await resettlement, said Azerbaijan Foreign
Ministry spokesman Bagirov, who did not give his first name.
   Others have been placed in new jobs and housing all over the
Azerbaijan, he said, although officials are still trying to persuade
both Azerbaijani and Armenian refugees to return home.
   The refugee situation in neighboring Armenia is much worse, since
the 90,000 Armenians who fled Azerbaijan have been joined by half a
million left homeless by the devastating Dec. 7 earthquake.
   Previous figures refugees, issued in November, said about 75,000
Armenians and 75,000 Azerbaijanis had fled to their homelands.
   Ethnic violence between the Moslem Azerbaijanis and the Christian
Armenians has torn the two southern Soviet republics for the past
year, and the latest outbreak starting in November killed 43 people,
according to today's Pravda.
   Bagirov said Baku, the Azerbaijani capital, was calm. The
atmosphere in the city was described as ``explosive'' during ethnic
unrest just before the quake.
   However, chief investigator Gen. Lt. V.K. Pankin of the national
Ministry of Interior told Pravda today, ``The situation is still
complicated.''
   His department has sent staffers from Moscow and elsewhere in the
Soviet Union to assist Azerbaijani law enforcement personnel to
ensure correct investigation of crimes, he told Pravda.
   Several Armenian prosecutors were fired this week for failing to
fulfill their duties.
   Authorities have begun filing criminal charges against those who
committed acts of violence during the riots, including murder and
arson, Pankin said. For example, one teahouse manager has been
arrested for inciting teen-agers to riot and carry an Islamic flag
in demonstrations, he said.
   In Baku, authorities continue to detain 100 to 200 people a night
for curfew violations, Bagirov said. On Friday, for example, 104
people were held for violating the curfew and four were detained for
inciting ethnic dissension where a curfew has been imposed.
   About 15,000 Armenians have returned to Baku after fleeing at the
height of the violence and daily demostrations by Azerbaijani
nationalists, Bagirov said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
