<FIRST>r a PM-NiceInmates     01-07 0150</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nice Inmates,0153</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jail Inmates Go To Cells After Guard Passes Out</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jail guard passed out while 48 inmates
were in a common dayroom, and the inmates, after calling for help,
locked themselves in their cells, authorities said.
   The inmates were given ice cream at their next meal for following
the correct emergency procedure, which was shown during a jail
orientation film, said Jail Commander Bob Conroy.
   Conroy said Santa Clara County's newest jail was designed to
foster better conditions by having officers mingle with inmates.
   The incident occurred Tuesday morning when the lone correctional
officer on duty, Veronica Foley, passed out because of a suspected
virus.
   One inmate picked up a red emergency phone and explained the
situation to officers in the building's central control room. Then
the prisoners, all male, went back to their cells and closed the
doors, Conroy said.
