<FIRST>r i PM-India-Sikh 1stLd-Writethru   01-07 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India-Sikh, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0429,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sikh Radicals Kill 10 Hindus in Punjab</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with railway station set on fire.
Pickup 7th graf pvs, ``Sikh militants...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEEPAK SHARMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sikh militants shot and killed 10 Hindus
and set fire to a railway station to avenge the hanging of two Sikhs
for the 1984 assassination of Prime Minister Indira Gandhi,
officials said today.
   Three or four Sikhs carrying AK-47 rifles raided four homes of
Hindu workers in Badowal village in Punjab on Friday, police chief
Govind Ram said.
   ``They separated the male members from others and shot them from
point-blank range,'' Ram said in a telephone interview. One woman
was injured in the firing when she tried to save her husband, he
said.
   The area is 20 miles south of the Sikh holy city of Amritsar.
   A note left by the killers said this was the first revenge
killing for the deaths of Satwant Singh and Kehar Singh, who were
hanged Friday in a New Delhi prison after their conviction for
assassinating Mrs. Gandhi.
   The note threatened more massacres in the state, Ram said.
   Also in apparent revenge for the hangings, a group of radicals
set fire to the Alab railway station in Punjab's Sangrur district on
Friday night, said officials in Chandigarh, the state capital. After
also damaging furniture at the station, the attackers fled, said the
officials, who demanded anonymity.
   Sikh militants had threatened widespread massacres of Hindus in
retaliation for the executions.
   Tens of thousands of police and paramilitary troops were deployed
across northern India to check outbreaks of secterian violence,
authorities said.
   The latest killings brought this week's death toll blamed on the
militants in the northern state of Punjab to at least 40. Last year,
2,400 people were killed in Sikh violence in the state.
   Mrs. Gandhi was slain in apparent revenge for the Indian army's
June 1984 raid on Sikhism's holiest shrine, the Golden Temple in
Amritsar. The raid was to clear the temple of Sikh militants who
were entrenched there.
   About 1,200 people, mainly Sikhs, died in the operation.
   Sikh militants have fought since 1982 for a separate nation in
India's north. They claim discrimination by Hindus, who make up more
than 80 percent of India's 880 million people.
</TEXT>
