<FIRST>u i PM-PLO-Embassies     01-07 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-PLO-Embassies,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jordan, China, Qatar Upgrade PLO Missions To Embassies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMAL HALABY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jordan, China and Qatar announced today they
will upgrade Palestine Liberation Organization missions in their
capitals to embassies, bolstering PLO chairman Yasser Arafat's peace
initiative.
   Eight countries now have given embassy status to the PLO. The
others are Saudi Arabia, Algeria, Bahrain, Iraq and the United Arab
Emirates.
   They are among about 70 countries that have recognized the
independent Palestinian state proclaimed in November by the
Palestine National Council, the PLO's parliament-in-exile.
   Boundaries of the still-symbolic Palestinian state have not been
defined. Official Radio Jordan said that at King Hussein's
direction, ``Jordan has decided to consider the PLO office in Jordan
the embassy of the state of Palestine.'' PLO sources said Arafat
would lay the embassy's cornerstone in Amman today.
   China's Xinhua News Agency quoted a Foreign Ministry spokesman as
saying Beijing's move will strengthen friendly relations between the
Chinese and Palestinian people.
   China long has been a supporter of the PLO and other Arab causes.
It says it will not normalize relations with Israel until Tel Aviv
returns land seized in the 1967 Israel-Arab war.
   Qatar's Foreign Ministry said the PLO office in Doha was upgraded
because of the Persian Gulf state's desire to ``bolster the national
legitimate rights of the Palestinian people, especially their right
to self-determination and establishing their independent state on
their national soil.''
   Leaders of the 13-month-old Palestinian uprising in the
Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza today called on European
countries to upgrade PLO offices there to embassy status.
   France on Thursday elevated the PLO's representation in Paris to
``General Delegation of Palestine.'' That fell short of diplomatic
recognition but still was considered a significant political
response to Arafat's moderate policies.
   Earlier today, Hussein met Arafat at the government guest house
in Amman to review ``the challenges facing the Arab community in
addition to bilateral relations,'' Jordan's official Petra news
agency reported. Jordan's prime minister, Zaid Rifai, was present
with several PLO executive committee members.
</TEXT>
