<DOCNO> AP890107-0066 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-07-89 1039EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Afghanistan     01-07 0499</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Envoy Says Moscow's Support For Kabul Non-Negotiable</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Deputy Foreign Minister Yuli
Vorontsov said today Moscow would ``find a way'' to support Kabul's
communist government after the withdrawal of the Red Army from
Afghanistan.
   Vorontsov told reporters a broad-based government ``representing
all the political forces of Afghanistan'' is the only way to
guarantee peace after the remaining 50,000 Soviet troops depart. The
Soviets are to withdraw by Feb. 15.
   The Soviet envoy dismissed claims by Moslem insurgents, as well
as Pakistani and Western analysts, that the ruling People's
Democratic Party of Afghanistan will be toppled once Soviet troops
leave.
   ``It will survive in its own right and you will know it after the
withdrawal of the Soviet forces,'' said Vorontsov. ``We will be
supporting them (Kabul communists) if there is no broad-based
government. We will support the regime in Kabul as the legal
government of the Republic of Afghanistan.
   ``We will find the way,'' said Vorontsov. ``We will tell you
later.'' He refused to elaborate further.
   Afghan guerrillas, who have been fighting the Soviet-backed
government for 10 years, have promised to establish a council to
choose a transitional government.
   ``If that's going to be only a one-sided council there is no
value in it,'' said Vorontsov.
   The alliance of seven Afghan guerrilla groups headquartered in
Pakistan has said no Afghan communists will be allowed to
participate in their council.
   Pakistan, which is giving refuge to more than 3 million Afghans,
also dismissed the participation of the People's Democratic Party of
Afghanistan in a postwar government.
   However, Vorontsov said the People's Democratic Party ``has all
the right to participate as a political force in that broad-based
government.
   ``They must be realistic,'' he said of the guerrillas. ``By
puffing and huffing they will not be able to destroy the house of
the present regime, if we take the words of the famous fairy tale
about the three little pigs.''
   Vorontsov said the February withdrawal deadline would be met
unless the guerrillas attack departing Soviet soldiers.
   ``It could be delayed if there were all out fighting on Soviet
forces, if there were attacks on Soviet forces withdrawing,'' said
Vorontsov. ``They will fight back to defend and will not withdraw.
   ``The Soviet soldiers are not running for their lives,'' he said.
   The Kremlin sent more than 100,000 Soviet soldiers into
Afghanistan in December 1979. Last April, Moscow agreed to withdraw
them by Feb. 15. Half had left by August.
   Vorontsov suggested the warring factions should look to the
United Nations to resolve the deadlock over Afghan's future
government.
   ``They have an important role to play, even more important than
ours,'' he said of the United Nations.
   Vorontsov's diplomatic mission began in early December when he
met Pakistan-based guerrillas in Saudi Arabia. The only significant
agreement to come out of that meeting was a decision to hold the
Islamabad talks. The only agreement this time was to hold more talks.
</TEXT>
