<FILEID>AP-NR-01-07-89 1056EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-CampaignReform     01-07 0805</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Campaign Reform,800</SECOND>
<HEAD>Clamor Rising for Overhaul of Campaign Finance System</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   From lawmakers on Capitol Hill to their
reform-minded critics and even well heeled lobbyists, a growing
chorus of influential voices is calling for an overhaul of the
nation's campaign finance system.
   House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, has campaign finance reform
near the top of his agenda for the new Congress as does Rep. Bob
Michel of Illinois, the Republican leader.
   And change is being urged by Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole,
R-Kan., whose GOP forces used a stubborn filibuster to kill a
Democratic election-money package in the last Congress.
   Senate Democrats have no formal agenda yet, but their new
majority leader, George Mitchell, D-Maine, favors change, and the
leader of the reform forces, Sen. David Boren, D-Okla., is ready to
renew his fight in 1989.
   There is optimism at Common Cause, the self-described citizens'
lobby, which wants to substitute public financing for individual and
special interest money in the quarter-billion-dollar plus business
of winning seats in Congress.
   ``It's going all the way to the top,'' says Fred Wertheimer,
Common Cause president. ``There's a different dynamic now. An awful
lot of Republicans are upset with the present system and talking
about need for change. There's an unusual opportunity for 1989.''
   Joining in the push are some people Common Cause wants to send to
the election sidelines, for example Bill Baer, a senior
partner-lobbyist in Arnold &amp; Porter, one of Washington's big league
law firms.
   ``Things have gotten out of hand,'' says Baer, who heads the
150-member Lobbyists and Lawyers for Campaign Finance Reform.
   Baer says there is deep and growing dissatisfaction over the
seemingly endless congressional fundraising events _ sometimes as
many as 10 in one night _ at which lobbyists fete candidates with
$2,000 contributions from political action committees operated by
industry, labor and ideological groups.
   The final tabulations for the 1987-8 election cycle haven't been
made by the Federal Election Commission. But the FEC says that
through last Sept. 30, PAC money continued to grow both in total
dollars and in comparison to campaign contributions from individuals.
   For the period, PACs pumped $35.7 million into all Senate
campaigns, up 1.7 percent over the corresponding 21 months of the
1985-6 cycle. They provided more than one-fifth of the $159.8
million given to Senate candidates.
   PACs provided one of every three dollars given to House
candidates, or about $73.7 million of the $214.4 million
contributed. The PAC money was nearly 24 percent higher than in the
first 21 months of the 1985-6 cycle.
   As in past years, incumbents fared better than their challengers
in the scramble for PAC dollars. Senators got $5.17 for every $1
contributed to challengers. In the House it was 10 to one in favor
of incumbents.
   When the votes were counted, all but six of the 411 House members
seeking reelection received another term.
   Under consideration are spending limits that would slow or halt
the rapidly rising cost of campaigns. Provisions could be included
involving phone-bank support that labor gives far more readily to
Democrats. And lawmakers are puzzling over what to do about huge
sums in little-controlled and unreported collected by the national
parties.
   Republicans have opposed altering the system for more than a
decade, thinking that they benefit more from the status quo. But
Democrats are getting more PAC money. Their fund-raising among
individuals is catching up with that of the the GOP.
   The Democratic Party already has pulled even in the so-called
``soft money'' race to put the bite on corporations and people who
can afford a $100,000 contribution not covered by FEC limits. And
labor continues to favor Democrats.
   Although Wertheimer is optimistic about action in the 101st
Congress, he sees ``a tough battle because individuals who benefit
from the current system, incumbents, will be writing the new rules.''
   Aides say House leaders want to negotiate a bipartisan bill. But
House Whip Tony Coelho, D-Calif., is warning that if necessary
Democrats will use their majority to pass their own package.
   The Senate is a different matter. If they keep their ranks
together as they did in the last Congress, the 45 Republicans can
again prevent a vote on campaign legislation they think favors
Democrats.
   ``We can have a bipartisan campaign finance reform bill or we'll
have no bill,'' says Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., Senate GOP
spokesman on the issue. ``We can stop it in the Senate or we can
stop it in the White House.''
   McConnell says that ``there's no middle ground on spending
limits.'' This puts him in direct conflict with Democrat Boren, who
last year cosponsored a package calling for voluntary spending
limits for Senate races.
   Even with this apparent basic difference, Boren says he sees some
unspecified ``bargaining room'' with McConnell and the Republicans.
</TEXT>
