<DOCNO> AP890107-0070 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-07-89 1058EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-SouthAfrica     01-07 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa,0392</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Blacks Killed in Natal Fighting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three black men were killed in
township violence in Natal province, police said today, bringing the
official death toll from fighting among black political factions
this year to 12.
   One of the three men killed Friday died when police shot into a
gang of men who were stoning a township home, police said.
   More than 1,000 people have died over the past 18 months in Natal
township fighting, chiefly between members of Mangosuthu Buthelezi's
Inkatha, a Zulu political organization, and supporters of the banned
United Democratic Front.
   Despite national emergency laws and restrictions enforced since
June 12, 1986, political unrest has continued at a reduced level,
particularly attacks on black policemen and homes of government
employees in black townships.
   But in the first week of 1989, political violence has been
reported every day. The events include stabbings and shootings in
Natal, mine explosions near Cape Town, gasoline bombings of
townships houses throughout the country, stonings of houses and
cars, and ambushes of policemen.
   However, the deaths and injuries and the numbers of incidents are
much lower than during the height of the unrest from 1984-86.
   Currently, most incidents occur in Natal, where Inkatha and the
United Democratic Front are fighting for control of segregated black
townships.
   The front supporters accuse police of siding with Buthelezi, whom
they regard as a collaborator because of his position as head of the
KwaZulu homeland government.
   Buthelezi accuses the front of supporting the bombing and
sabotage campaign of the outlawed African National Congress. He
disagrees with front policies supporting boycotts, sanctions and
strikes to end the apartheid policy of legal race separation.
   During the violence Friday, police said a group of blacks fired
at a another group, killing one man, in Mpumalanga township, where a
house was damaged by a gasoline bomb.
   Police said they killed one black man and arrested four men when
they opened fire with shotguns and pistols at a crowd of blacks who
were stoning a house in Haza township.
   The body of a black man who had been stabbed to death was found
at Taylor's Halt, police said, and another black man was shot and
wounded by an unidentified assailant in Imbali township.
</TEXT>
