<FILEID>AP-NR-01-07-89 1101EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru a0495 01-07 0583</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0495,0599</SECOND>
<HEAD>Radical Palestinians Form New Anti-PLO Coalition</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New 11th graf ``Last week, death...'' to provide background.
Pickup 11th graf pvs, ``Reports in Palestinian ....'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Radical Palestinians in the occupied territories
have formed a coalition of Moslem fundamentalists and pro-Syrian
factions opposed to PLO chief Yasser Arafat's recent peace overtures.
   The radical alliance on Friday issued a leaflet accusing Arafat
of ``selling out'' the cause when he recognized Israel and renounced
terrorism.
   Arab hospital officials said today that a Palestinian village
leader in the occupied lands was stabbed to death Friday by
unidentified assailants.
   Elsewhere, Israeli troops today shot and wounded 10 Palestinians
who attacked them with rocks, an Arab reporter said.
   Hospital officials said one of the wounded was a 16-year-old girl
who was in critical condition after being shot in the head in the
West Bank city of Nablus. Three other West Bank Arabs were shot and
wounded, while six were wounded in the southern Gaza Strip, Arab
reports and hospital officials said on condition of anonymity. The
military said it was checking the reports.
   Mahmoud Abdallah Hamoudah, the 57-year-old mukhtar or traditional
leader of the West Bank village of Qubeiba, died Friday of multiple
stab wounds, said a Ramallah hospital official.
   Israel Radio said Hamoudah was killed by a Palestinian mob that
attacked him at his home because he was suspected of working for
Israeli security forces.
   His two sons, Nasser Mahmoud ,22, and Walid, 29, were slightly
wounded in the attack, said the hospital official. They were treated
for head wounds and discharged. A military spokesman refused to
comment on the incident.
   Qubeiba is seven miles northwest of Jerusalem.
   Palestinians have killed more than a dozen suspected Palestinian
collaborators since the anti-Israeli revolt started 13 months ago.
They are among at least 347 Arabs and 14 Israelis who have died in
the uprising.
   Last week, death threats against Bethlehem mayor Elias Freij were
scrawled on walls in the town after he proposed a truce in the
Palestinian uprising. Also last week, a 25-year-old suspected
collaborator was killed in Jericho.
   Reports in Palestinian newspapers say pro-Syrian groups want to
install more radical leaders.
   In the occupied Gaza Strip, four refugee camps were under curfew
today, said an army spokesman who demanded anonymity.
   The United National Front in Occupied Palestine, as the radical
new coalition calls itself, said in its leaflet, ``We demand the
establishment of a militant leadership to replace the diminishing
leadership of Yasser Arafat.''
   The new faction includes members of Ahmed Jibril's Popular Front
For the Liberation Of Palestine-General Command and Abu Moussa's
breakaway faction of Arafat's mainstream Fatah group.
   ``There can be no reconciliation with the Israeli killers and no
negotiations with Zionist criminals,'' the document said. ``We
oppose any kind of political settlement, whatever its source, and
consider negotiation with the enemy to be grave treason and an
unforgivable crime.''
   It called for a new Palestine National Council to be led by
advocates of armed struggle. The Palestine National Council in
November implicitly recognized Israel in a declaration of an
independent Palestinian homeland.
   Israeli officials did not accept the implicit recognition, and
maintain the Palestine Liberation Organization still is dedicated to
destroying Israel.
   Pro-Syrian Palestinians said the new Palestinian alliance
resulted from increased collaboration between extremist factions
over the past few months.
   ``The PLO has been moving from one mistake to another. We totally
reject the PLO's political compromises,'' said Sufian Khatib, a
Jerusalem physician opposed to Arafat.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
