<DOCNO> AP890107-0075 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-07-89 1121EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Yugoslavia     01-07 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Yugoslavia,0277</SECOND>
<HEAD>Croatian Leading Candidate For New Yugoslav Premier</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ante Markovic, a strong supporter of
market- oriented reforms and a leader of the republic of Croatia, is
the leading candidate to become Yugoslavia's new premier, newspapers
said today.
   Premier Branko Mikulic and his government resigned Dec. 30 after
being criticized for failing to curb the country's 250 percent
annual inflation rate and other economic problems. It was the first
time the government of Yugoslavia resigned since the communists took
power after World War II.
   ``The most serious candidate to become Yugoslavia's new premier
is Ante Markovic,'' said the Vecernje Novosti daily.
   Mikulic is to stay in office as caretaker premier until the
nine-member federal presidency names a new premier, probably by the
end of January.
   The new Yugoslav Cabinet, which is expected to be installed in
February, will probably include Foreign Minister Budimir Loncar and
Defense Minister Veljko Kadijevic, both of whom resigned, the
newspaper said.
   Markovic, an electrical engineer who had managed a large Yugoslav
company, is currently a member of the collective presidency of the
northern republic of Croatia. He has often advocated radical
market-oriented changes and demanded reforms in the country's
political system.
   Mikulic also has called for economic reforms, but he did not
favor major changes in Yugoslavia's communist political system.
   During a recent Communist Party meeting, Markovic said the
authorities ``should not scare Yugoslavs by saying reforms would
bring social upheavals and unemployment, since we already face such
problems today.''
   Workers last year staged a record 1,400 strikes, and many
Yugoslavs have called for a multi-party political system.
</TEXT>
