<FIRST>r i AM-BargeFire     01-07 0165</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Barge Fire,0167</SECOND>
<HEAD>Barge Fires Kill Two Firefighter, Leave Six Missing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire broke out on two oil barges in the Yangtze
River, and at least two firefighters were killed trying to put out
the blazes and six were missing, a news report said Saturday.
   The fire began Monday on a barge anchored near Wuhan, about 700
miles south of Beijing, and spread to a second barge, the Xinhua
News Agency said. One of the barges was still burning Saturday,
according to the report.
   One firefighter was found dead Monday, and the second body was
found Saturday, Xinhua said.
   The two barges carried almost 34,000 tons of oil, Xinhua said. It
said the barge still burning was anchored to prevent it from
drifting down the river to Wuhan, a major metropolitan area.
   The cause of the fire was not known. Initial reports said fires
broke out simultaneously on the two barges and caused an explosion
that spread burning oil across the river.
