<DOCNO> AP890107-0084 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-07-89 1219EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-MissouriSpill     01-07 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Missouri Spill,0389</SECOND>
<HEAD>Missouri Oil Spill Possibly Linked To Problem At Refinery</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Oil Spill Impact, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shell Oil Co. officials said a pipeline rupture
that sent 840,000 gallons of oil into the Gasconade River last month
may have been caused by a malfunction at an Illinois refinery that
temporarily increased pressure in the line.
   Shell spokesman Tony Canino said Friday that pressure increased
in the pipeline laid in 1948 while valves at a refinery in Wood
River, Ill., 170 miles east of the spill site in central Missouri,
were switching some crude oil from the Shell pipeline into another
line operated by Marathon Oil Co.
   Canino said company officials have not determined what caused the
malfunction.
   The oil from the spill, one of the worst inland spills in U.S.
history, made its way from the Gasconade to the Missouri River, and
from there to the Mississippi.
   Meanwhile, a spokeswoman for the U.S. Department of
Transportation said a federal inspector visited the spill site last
week to determine if Shell violated any regulations in its operation
of the 435-mile pipeline, which runs from Cushing, Okla., to
Roxanna, Ill.
   The oil lost in the Shell spill is more than three times larger
than the amount lost in all pipeline accidents in 1987, the last
year for which figures are available, said the spokeswoman, Suzette
Paes.
   The oil erupted from a 35-foot rupture in a buried pipeline near
the Gasconade River, about 140 miles west of St. Louis.
   Also Friday, Anheuser Busch Cos. announced that it had recalled
1,500 of 2,000 bottlers and brewers laid off Tuesday when production
shut down after tasters noticed an oily aroma to the water used for
brewing the beer. Water samples taken Wednesday by the state
Department of Natural Resources turned up no traces of oil or
related chemicals.
   In a statement, Andrew J. Steinhubl, senior vice president of
brewing, said the company ``would return gradually to full
production and full employment.''
   St. Louis water department officials have said that while the
water from city taps might taste and smell oily for a few days,
there was no danger. Extra steps were taken in treating water taken
from the Missouri and Mississippi as the oil spill moved past the
city.
</TEXT>
