<DOCNO> AP890107-0085 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-07-89 1228EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Emperor-Ceremony     01-07 0524</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Emperor-Ceremony,0539</SECOND>
<HEAD>Akihito Ascends Chrysanthemum Throne In Ancient Ceremony</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With AM-Hirohito, Bjt ^By ERIC TALMADGE</BYLINE>
<UNK>Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a short, silent ceremony soon after the death of
his father, Emperor Akihito on Saturday ascended the Chrysanthemum
Throne and received the mythic symbols of imperial legitimacy _ a
sword and jewels.
   The ancient ceremony began when the new emperor, clad in black
morning coat and gray trousers and accompanied by six male members
of the imperial family, entered the Matsu no Ma Hall of the Imperial
Palace.
   For the first time, reporters were allowed to witness the somber
ritual, which later was broadcast on national television.
   Journalists were led through dimly lit, concrete tunnels to the
palace, where they watched through tinted windows that hid them from
those at the ceremony.
   It lasted just four minutes.
   Taking his place before a purple and gold folding screen and
high-backed wooden chair bearing the imperial chrysanthemum crest,
Akihito stood facing the official witnesses _ Prime Minister Noboru
Takeshita, 19 Cabinet ministers, the four heads of Parliament and
two Supreme Court judges.
   The government leaders later were joined by top Imperial
Household Agency officials and chamberlains. All wore morning coats
and black ties.
   With bows, three palace officials presented the seals and two
encased objects of the regalia _ a sword and jewels _ then placed
them on short wooden tables before the emperor. The third regalia
item, a mirror, is kept at a shrine on the palace grounds.
   The regalia, which have deep religious significance to followers
of Japan's native Shinto religion, have never been displayed in
public and were encased throughout the rite.
   After exchanging bows with those present, Akihito left the room
preceded by the sword bearer and followed by the chamberlain
carrying the jewels. The imperial and state seals, carried in two
purple pouches, were removed after other members of the imperial
family had left.
   For centuries the regalia have symbolized the divine origin of
the world's oldest imperial family.
   According to legend, the mirror was used by the deities to lure
the sun goddess Amaterasu out of self-imposed seclusion on the High
Celestial Plain and the jewels were given to her after she emerged.
   The sword was a token of repentance by her brother, who drew it
from a giant eight-tailed, eight-headed snake he killed after being
banished from the divine highland for misconduct.
   Amaterasu later gave the regalia to her grandson, Ninigi no
Mikoto, before sending him to conquer the Japanese islands. He
passed them on to Jimmu, another descendant of the sun goddess who
by legend was Japan's first ruler.
   Today, the supposed original mirror is kept at the Grand Shrine
of Ise, the center of Shinto sun goddess worship 200 miles southwest
of Tokyo. The ``original'' sword is at the Atsuta Shrine in Nagoya,
central Japan, and the ``original'' jewels, said to be comma-shaped
stones, are kept at the Imperial Palace in Tokyo.
   Replicas of the sword and mirror, themselves ancient, are used in
imperial ascension ceremonies.
   Until his death Saturday, Emperor Hirohito slept in a room where
the jewels and replica sword are stored.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890107-0086 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-07-89 1229EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Libya 4thLd-Writethru a0497 01-07 0836</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Libya, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0497,0859</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Gadhafi Calls For Talks With U.S. About Chemical Plant Controversy</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf pvs with new grafs 7-9 ``The United States...''
to update with U.S. response. Picks up 8th graf pvs ``Gadhafi's five-minute-long...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRY LEONARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRIPOLI, Libya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moammar Gadhafi today called for direct
negotiations with the United States to resolve a dispute over a
Libyan factory U.S. officials claim was built to produce chemical
weapons.
   The Libyan leader made the statement at Tripoli's best hotel,
where he arrived unexpectedly to speak to foreign reporters. It was
his first public appearance since two U.S. Navy jets shot down two
Libyan MiGs over the Mediterranean Sea on Wednesday.
   ``America must understand that her policy of surrounding us and
using force against us will absolutely fail,'' Gadhafi said,
speaking softly in Arabic.
   ``They must negotiate with Libya directly and they should sit at
the negotiating table with Libya without their weapons to achieve
peace in the Mediterranean,'' he said. He was ringed by bodyguards
during his appearance in a hotel lobby lounge.
   ``I think the Bush administration will be able to do this because
they will have learned their lessons of the previous administration.
There have been enough lessons. They will have learned that force
does not pay, especially with Libya,'' Gadhafi said.
   ``We will not respond to force, only to politeness and direct
negotiations.''
   The United States brushed aside Gadhafi's call for direct
negotiations. A senior U.S. official, attending a chemical warfare
conference in Paris, said, ``Communications is not the problem, the
problem is Libyan policy.''
   But the official, who briefed reporters on condition of
anonymity, also said, ``I am not ruling anything in or out.''
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz said Thursday the United
States had been able to stay in touch with Libya through
intermediaries.
   Gadhafi's five-minute-long statement was translated into English
by a Libyan who works for the Information Ministry.
   The Libyan leader's curly hair was topped by a black, wool
pillbox hat. He wore a maroon-and-blue sweater, covered by a brown
wool cape, to protect him from Tripoli's rainy weather.
   Asked about the U.S. pressures on his country, Gadhafi vowed
never to bow to the Americans, ``even if this confrontation lasts 1
million years.''
   The unexpected sight of a smiling Gadhafi in the hotel set off
chaos. Journalists and camera crews knocked over potted plants,
scrambled atop chairs and climbed over a two-story-high ornamental
fountain inside the lobby.
   Sources in the capital said Gadhafi had not been seen in public
for several weeks, and there was speculation he had fled in fear of
a U.S. attack.
   Tensions between the United States and Libya have increased
because of U.S. allegations that Libya has built a chemical weapons
factory in Rabta, 60 miles from the capital.
   Libya has insisted the plant will manufacture medicine. President
Reagan has said he could not rule out a military strike against the
site.
   In 1986, Gadhafi's headquarters in Tripoli was bombed by the
United States in to retaliate for Libya's alleged support for
terrorism.
   Gadhafi told reporters today that the administration of
President-elect George Bush ``should sit with Libya to discuss
face-to-face cases of dispute. Libya is absolutely against terrorism
but we are beside the just struggle for just causes.''
   He added: ``The Palestinian peoples' stuggle for a free Palestine
is a just struggle and we will never hesitate to support it.''
Gadhafi's regime came to power in 1969 with a coup that ousted a
Western-backed monarchy.
   ``Bush will have another lesson from the failure of America's
childish policies, which gain nothing,'' said Gadhafi.
   Gadhafi and other Libyan officials offered the United States a
one-time inspection of the Rabta plant, but the Reagan
administration rejected that offer, saying Libya could disguise the
plant for the inspection and then restore its chemical weapons'
capabilities.
   Gadhafi told reporters today: ``Libya will participate in all
negotiations to get rid of all weapons from ordinary guns to nuclear
bombs. America must get rid of its chemical and nuclear weapons
factories and cancel the `Star Wars' program,'' refering to U.S.
research for a space-based defense system.
   ``All nations of the world must agree to get rid of weapons and
settle for peace. If this does not happen, we have only
confrontation. Libya will never surrender and America will lose,''
said Gadhafi.
   ``Libya will accept the participation of any international
committee to inspect Israeli factories and factories in America,
Europe and any spot of the world,'' Gadhafi concluded in his
statement.
   On Friday, the Libyan government charged at a news conference and
in official media that its planes were overwhelmed Wednesday by 14
``hostile American aircraft.''
   A government spokesman maintained the U.S. report that two Navy
jets had acted in self-defense was ``a fabrication.''
   Washington provided the U.S. media with videotape taken by a U.S.
aircraft of the encounter and showed photographs to the U.N.
Security Council of what it said was a heavily armed Libyan plane
involved in the encounter.
</TEXT>
