<FIRST>r a AM-MissingWoman     01-07 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Missing Woman,0311</SECOND>
<HEAD>Farmer Finds Woman's Body After Sketch Of His Barn Telecast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TIFTON, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A farmer watching a television news report
about a missing woman recognized the sketch of a barn that was shown
as his own. He then went out and found her body buried nearby.
   The body found Friday was identified as that of Virginia Moore,
26, of Berrien County, said John Bankhead, a Georgia Bureau of
Investigation spokesman in Atlanta.
   William Earl Lynd, 33, of Berrien County, who had already been
charged in Ms. Moore's slaying, also faces a murder charge in the
Christmas Day shooting of a Detroit woman near Chesapeake, Ohio.
   Lynd had told authorities he buried Ms. Moore near a building off
Interstate 75, said Berrien County Sheriff Jerry Brogdon.
Authorities distributed a sketch of the building Thursday based on
those statements.
   Tift County farmer Clarence Smith said he saw the sketch on
television and recognized his barn. When he searched around it,
Smith found the body under about 9 inches of dirt, Bankhead said.
   Authorities had been searching for Ms. Moore's body along a
200-mile stretch of Interstate 75 between Atlanta and south
Georgia's Cook County. Tift County is just north of Cook County.
   State officials said Ms. Moore is believed to have been killed
Dec. 23, the day she disappeared from her home. Lynd was charged
based on a statement he made after surrendering Dec. 31.
   Lynd also is charged with killing Leslie JoAnn Starkey, 42, of
Detroit, who was shot Christmas Day in Ohio as she traveled to West
Virginia for a family gathering. She was able to describe her
attacker before she died Dec. 26.
   Lynd is being held without bond in the Berrien County jail. He
also is charged with auto theft in the disappearance of Ms. Moore's
car.
</TEXT>
