<DOCNO> AP890107-0089 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-07-89 1245EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     01-07 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HATTIESBURG, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A half-dozen students in an adult
literacy project were hesitant at first, but now they're all
published authors.
   The book of six stories, ``Fireside Memories,'' was mailed last
week to 200 people who helped keep the Hattiesburg Education
Literacy Project going during the past year.
   The 24-page book is partly a ``thank you'' to those who have
given time and money to the literacy project, but it's also a way to
get the students interested in writing, said Project Director Ron
Blackwell.
   When Blackwell and Tom Boss, volunteer coordinator for the
center, first proposed to students that they write stories for
publication, the answer was ``No way,'' Boss said.
   Some of the adult students don't want to let their friends and
coworkers know they have trouble reading, Boss said.
   But eventually, six students agreed to put their ideas in print.
Some wrote their stories alone, others dictated to a tutor.
   Tom Miller, who has been working with tutor Kathy Ballard for two
years, wrote poetically about colors of Christmas: ``With all of its
beauty of red, gold and silver and the pure white snow which stands
for God's pure love for us all.''
   ``We talked about writing what Christmas meant to him,'' Ballard
said. ``He came in with it, and it was written. It was not all in
complete sentences, but I didn't want to touch it; it was free
verse. The only things I changed were some possible spellings.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>STORRS, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   What would a legal document be without a few
``heretofores'' and ``forthwiths?''
   It probably would be better written and easier to understand,
says Minerva H. Neiditz, director of the University of Connecticut's
Institute of Writing, who is running a contest to find the best
legal brief written in Connecticut in 1988.
   For the contest, 900 law firms and state agencies have been asked
to submit their best appellate briefs filed in either state or
federal court. The deadline is Jan. 15, and Neiditz is hoping to
receive at least 100 entries.
   ``Lawyers have been my most difficult clients because they all
assume they can write. They're extremely sensitive to anyone
criticizing them,'' Nieditz said.
   ``There is a tremendous amount of extra verbiage and pomposity,''
she said. ``So, I thought it would be an exciting first project for
the institute to create this competition for the best legal brief.''
   Briefs will be screened initially by members of the UConn Law
Review. Then a panel of six judges will make the final selection.
   Some details of the contest are still to be worked out. For
instance, Neiditz doesn't know how many runners-up will be named,
she doesn't know when the winners will be announced, and she doesn't
know if cash prizes will be given, although she's hoping they will.
   In the event of a tie, Neiditz will cast the deciding vote.
</TEXT>
