<FIRST>r w PM-Reagan-Radio 1stLd-Writethru a0537 01-07 0564</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Reagan-Radio, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0537,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Touts 1990 Budget As `Responsible Plan'</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: ADDS 3 grafs to update with Wright response to Reagan address.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan touted his forthcoming budget
today as a ``responsible plan'' that will cut the deficit and assure
America's prosperity without raising taxes.
   ``I leave as I came _ dead set against any new taxes,'' Reagan
said in the next-to-last radio address of his presidency.
   The five-minute talk was taped on Friday because the president
entered Walter Reed Army Medical Center for surgery today to correct
a curvature of his left ring finger.
   The president's final spending plan is due out Monday, a $1.15
trillion budget that is said to propose the elimination of 82
government programs while protecting his two-term defense buildup.
It covers the 1990 fiscal year, which begins next Oct. 1.
   But since President-elect George Bush is slated to take office on
Jan. 20, Reagan's document has been branded in some quarters as
irrelevant.
   ``It's a responsible plan which cuts the deficit without touching
Social Security, weakening defense, or reducing benfits to the
needy,'' Reagan asserted. ``And the best news is that this budget
proves it can be done without raising your taxes.''
   ``Raising taxes would be the surest way to kill the economic
goose that lays the golden eggs,'' Reagan said.
   The president argued that his plan will contain additional funds
for air safety, fighting crime, housing the poor, the war on drugs,
and the space program, as well as fighting Acquired Immune
Deficiency Syndrome, or AIDS.
   The president also warned that his defense buildup must be
maintained, saying, it is ``the price of peace and security for
America.''
   ``My fiscal year 1990 budget provides for the needy, does not
raise taxes, and by controlling the growth in spending, reduces the
deficit next year by nearly $70 billion,'' Reagan said.
   ``This budget is a realistic program which protects the working
families of America, provides adequate support for those who depend
on government and helps assure America's prosperity for years to
come,'' Reagan said.
   The president also put in a plug for his decision this week to
back the large pay raise for Congress, judges and top executive
branch officials that has been recommended by a presidential
commission.
   ``We must be willing to pay for excellence in government or risk
a government run only by people of wealth or by those beholden to
special interests,'' Regan said.
   The 50 percent pay raise will be come law automatically unless
each house of Congress rejects it by Feb. 8. The plan includes a ban
on outside speaking fees and other certain income and will formally
be sent to the Congress with Reagan's budget on Monday.
   Giving the Democratic response to Reagan's radio speech was House
Speaker Jim Wright of Texas, who expressed hopes for ``a new era of
cooperation and good feelings'' between Congress and the White House.
   Speaking about Bush, Wright said, ``we in the House leadership
are eager to help him attain his announced goal of wider access for
all Americans to education, to child care, to affordable housing and
to a cleaner environment.''
   ``We in Congress hope that the next administration, together with
us, will usher in a new era of cooperation and good feelings between
the legislative and executive branches of government,'' Wright said.
</TEXT>
