<DOCNO> AP890107-0097 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-07-89 1433EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-LouisianaDeseg     01-07 0642</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Louisiana Deseg,0661</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Year Brings Integration, Ending 36-Year-Old Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENSBURG, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Black and white students are in the same
public schools for the first time in St. Helena Parish, after
officials settled a 36-year-old integration lawsuit, the nation's
oldest.
   ``The biggest problem has been kids not finding their
classrooms,'' said Malcolm Mizell, one of two administrators sharing
responsibility for the new consolidated high school, after classes
began Friday.
   ``It's working smoother than anybody thought it would,'' agreed
Willie Johnson, the other co-supervisor. Mizell was principal at
all-white Greensburgh High School and Johnson was principal at Fifth
Ward Elementary, a predominantly black school.
   Although St. Helena Parish's high school students all are going
to class in what used to be Greensburg High, it will be next fall
before their classes are integrated, officials said. For this
semester, they have the same classmates and teachers they had when
the year began.
   Friday was the first day of class under an integration plan
proposed by the school board and approved Dec. 22 by U.S. District
Judge John Parker.
   Parker made his ruling settling the nation's oldest pending
desegregation lawsuit after two days of hearings, during which white
parents demonstration against consolidation and black parents
demonstrated for it.
   ``There is no question the St. Helena School Board has been
operating in violation of the Constitution of the United States,''
Parker said in his ruling. ``The board now has come with its own
proposal to consolidate all schools in the parish and this means
desegregation will be accomplished.
   ``In some areas, these schools are not fit for a doghouse,'' the
judge added.
   The suit was filed in 1952 by John Hall, whose 14 children all
attended black schools, and the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People. That was even before the U.S. Supreme
Court's landmark ruling in the case of Brown vs. the Board of
Education of Topeka, Kan., that ruled that segregated schools are
inherently unequal.
   About 70 percent of the 2,040 children now in public school are
black, although the parish population is about 51 percent black. St.
Helena Parish is northeast of Baton Rouge, the state capital.
   The school board, saying it could no longer afford segregated
schools, combined seven schools into three _ one for kindergarten
through fourth-grade students, one for grades 5-8 and the high
school.
   ``Most of the adjustments are at the elementary school,'' said
Perry Spears, the parish's first black superintendent of schools and
one of only three black superintendents among Louisiana's 64 parish
(county) and two city school systems.
   The elementary level also was where most of the obvious problems
were. Kindergarten and the first four grades were consolidated at
what had been St. Helena Elementary _ a predominantly black school.
Three other elementary schools were closed, two for blacks and one
for whites.
   ``Why couldn't they have waited? I went into two classrooms and
neither have lights. They have wires all over,'' said Shirley
Blackwell, whose second- and fourth-grade sons had attended a closed
white school.
   Kindergarten teacher Kim Chadwick, who came from a closed school,
said her new classroom had no heat, one of her two windows wouldn't
open, there were no electrical outlets, painting was incomplete,
clothes racks weren't up, floors hadn't been cleaned and the play
area was so full of cars that recess was canceled.
   Spears said all of the parish's schools are substandard, but the
four closed schools were the worst.
   ``I think today is excellent for a start, and I expect to see
changes of attitudes in the next couple of days,'' the
superintendent said.
   Larry Self, a senior who had attended predominately black St.
Helena High, said there hadn't been any conflicts.
   ``I play basketball and that'll work out once we get to know each
other _ when we learn each other's moves,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
