<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     01-07 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0418</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Die in Battles between Rival Shiite Militiamen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four fighters were killed and 12 civilians
wounded in battles Saturday between rival Shiite Moslem militias in
west Beirut's bomb-scarred commercial district and south Lebanon, a
police spokesman said.
   An uneasy calm prevailed Saturday afternoon following the clashes
between the pro-Syrian Amal, which means Hope, and Iranian-backed
Hezbollah, or Party of God.
   Three fighters were killed and eight people wounded in fierce
Beirut street battles, said the spokesman who cannot be named under
police rules.
   The two groups also dueled with howitzers and mortars 30 miles
southeast of Beirut, killing one combatant and wounding four people,
he said.
   The new casualties brought the casualty toll to 33 killed and 92
wounded the Dec. 31 outbreak of the latest round of violence between
the rival militias.
   Shell explosions accompanied by staccato bursts of machine-gun
fire echoed across Beirut through the night as Amal militiamen
launched hit-and-run attacks on Hezbollah positions near the western
edge of the civil war Green Line that divides the capital into
Moslem and Christian sectors.
   Hezbollah, according to the spokesman, responded by shelling
Amal-controlled districts of west Beirut to ``ease the pressure on
its fighters.''
   Syrian troops armed with AK-47 assault rifles and
rocket-propelled grenade launchers moved into the disputed area
before dawn and enforced a cease-fire, the spokesman said.
   In south Lebanon's Iklim al-Tiffah, or Apple Province, Amal
gunners shelled Hezbollah fighters with howitzers in the villages of
Jbaa, Jarjou, Arab Saleem, Louwaizeh and Ein Bouswar on the
northwestern edge of Israel's self-proclaimed security zone.
   The police spokesman said Hezbollah answered by shelling Amal's
supply lines.
   ``No change of positions was reported in the region. The fighting
died down early in the morning,'' he said.
   The Dec. 31 clash shattered a Syrian-brokered cease-fire. The
Nov. 27 cease-fire ended six days of Amal-Hezbollah fighting in
which 40 people were killed and 87 wounded.
   For more than nine months, the two factions have been fighting
for dominance of the 1 million Shiites who make up Lebanon's largest
sect.
   Amal flushed Hezbollah out of most of south Lebanon in a four-day
crackdown in April that killed 62 people and wounded 150.
   The militias fought a fierce 22-day battle in the slums of south
Beirut in May, killing 286 people and wounding 972 by police count.
That confrontation also ended with Syrian intervention.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
