<FILEID>AP-NR-01-07-89 1455EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Democrats-Text     01-07 0717</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Democrats-Text,720</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is the text of the Democratic response to
President Reagan's radio address Saturday, given by House Speaker
Jim Wright of Texas:
   Good afternoon. This is Jim Wright. In 13 days, President Reagan
will complete his eight years as our nation's chief executive. I
know I speak for all Americans in wishing for Mr. Reagan the
blessings of health and happiness, as much rest as he wants and as
much work as he wants, and a full and productive life in his
retirement. For President-elect Bush, all of us wish success in his
mighty endeavor _ the strength, the vision, courage and ability
required in that most important office on Earth, and the finest
blessings of God.
   Let us work as Americans to begin the new year in a cooperative
spirit. In a nation where free men and women think for themselves,
unanimity is never possible; it probably isn't even desirable. But
when we let the larger things that unite us transcend the lesser
concerns that divide us, our nation can achieve the basic unity
essential in dealing with foreign countries.
   As a spokesman for the loyal opposition and leader of the House
of Representatives, one who has often disagreed with the domestic
priorities of the Reagan administration, I want to express thanks as
an American to this administration for improving relations with the
Soviet Union, for helping to abate the crisis in the Persian Gulf,
and for encouraging the growth and sustenance of political freedom
in countries throughout the world.
   In most areas of our foreign policy, the Congress and the
administration have worked together. The only exceptions were how to
deal with South Africa and with Nicaragua. During the new
administration, I earnestly hope that we will be able to achieve
true bipartisanship in every area of our foreign policy, and I
pledge to President-elect Bush the unstinting cooperation of the
congressional leadership in seeking that end.
   On the domestic front, our nation struggles to overcome three
deficits: the budget deficit, the trade deficit, and the social
deficit, caused by the growing difficulty for average Americans in
trying to pay for such basic necessities as housing, higher
education and health care. Now we cannot expect to vanquish those
evils entirely in this coming year. But if we have the will, we can
make significant progress against all three deficits. Both of our
political parties are publicly committed to doing so.
   By working together, we can help our new president fulfill his
announced promise of a ``kinder, gentler'' America. We in the House
leadership are eager to help him attain his announced goals of wider
access for all Americans to education, to child care, to affordable
housing, and to a cleaner environment. Working together, we can
remove the scourge of drugs from our streets and from our schools.
We have made significant progress in this bipartisan goal. Let us
work together now for full funding to make our pledge a reality.
Working together, we can pass a clean air bill this year. Let's make
that one of our objectives.
   By working together, we can clean up the murky areas of campaign
financing, broaden the base of small individual contributors and
reduce the influence of special interests. This deserves our
commitment, and I now invite a joint commitment.
   By working together, we can steadily reduce and eventually
eliminate the annual budget deficits that threaten our economic
future. Both Democrats and Republicans made contributions last year
to landmark trade legislation. Let us not abandon that effort until
America attains the objective of a revived industrial base.
   This is going to be a very busy and productive year in Congress.
I am determined that as far as the speaker can influence the
schedule, we're going to perform our work on time. As we did last
year, the House will pass all of our regular appropriations bills
before the beginning of the August recess.
   Now we in Congress hope that the next administration, together
with us, will usher in a new era of cooperation and good feelings
between the Legislative and Executive branches of government.
America faces daunting challenges, but by working together, we can
assure that America's future will shine just as brightly as our past.
   Thank you for listening, and good afternoon.
</TEXT>
