<HEAD>Creator of TV's `Roseanne' Leaves Show After Tension With The Star</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top producer of the popular ABC television
comedy series ``Roseanne'' has left the show citing ``creative
tensions'' with the star, comedian Roseanne Barr, the show's
publicist said.
   Matt Williams, one of three executive producers of the most
successful program of this fall's television season, walked off the
show late Friday, publicist David Brokaw said in a statement.
   The statement said the tensions were ``between the executive
producers and Roseanne Barr.'' Williams was the only executive
producer to leave.
   ``Roseanne,'' which stars the sarcastic comedian as a middle
American housewife and mother who works at a factory, has
consistently been a hit with viewers. For the past two weeks, it has
beat out ``The Cosby Show'' for the No. 1 spot in the Nielsen
ratings.
   The remaining executive producers, Marcy Carcey and Tom Werner,
said in a statement that Barr was given creative control over her
own character, and that her insight into working women and
housewives is what appealed to the general public.
   Calls seeking comment from Barr placed to Brokaw's office and to
ABC Entertainment went unanswered Saturday.
