<FILEID>AP-NR-01-07-89 1548EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-AutoShow     01-07 0569</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auto Show,0589</SECOND>
<HEAD>Auto Show Opens With Smoother, Sleeker Cars and Trucks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Under all the glitz at Saturday's opening of the
North American International Auto Show are 700 cars and trucks
showing that rounded shapes have taken charge and the rolling box is
becoming a thing of the past.
   ``It's obvious that everyone is hitting the aerodynamics heavy,''
Ron Dalton of Ann Arbor said looking over the displays at the show,
which runs through Jan. 15.
   ``Just look at the Cadillacs,'' said Dalton, who added he prefers
Fords. ``They're starting to soften the lines even on the big ones.
They aren't bulky boxes anymore.''
   Automakers talk a lot about performance, suspension and safety,
but most American car shoppers look for other things, said analyst
Ron Glantz of Montgomery Securities in San Francisco.
   ``People buy cars for three reasons: price, looks and
reliability,'' he said.
   And appearance is what an auto show is all about. There are no
test drives and some of the cars can't even be touched.
   There are new versions of old cars, like the Oldsmobile Cutlass
series, and completely new cars, like the Ford Thunderbird and
Mercury Cougar. There are traditional luxury cars, like Cadillac and
Mercedes-Benz. And there are high-powered sports cars, like Jaguar
and a new Corvette.
   There are two new imported luxury car lines at the show _
Toyota's Lexus and Nissan's Infiniti _ which won't be in showrooms
until next fall.
   A common thread is exterior design.
   The lines between the roofs and windshields and doors are barely
noticeable. Rear windows flow smoothly into trunk lids, and
redesigned under-door panels add to a sleeker appearance.
   Smooth design also moved into the popular minivan segment, in
General Motors Corp.'s new line of plastic-body, all-purpose
vehicles for 1990, including the Pontiac Trans Sport, the Oldsmobile
Silhouette and the Chevrolet Lumina.
   ``I think that they are going to be dynamite vehicles,'' Glantz
said. ``There are a lot of advantages to having a plastic body _ you
don't have a rust problem and it resists minor dings.
   ``And some people just want to have something new-looking,'' he
added.
   ``Will an Oldsmobile buyer like it? That's a pretty traditional
buyer,'' Glantz said. ``But I tell you, the Pontiac buyer will love
it.''
   While watching a white Trans Sport revolve slowly on a turntable
at the show, Cheryl Boily of Windsor, Ontario, said, ``It's
definitely different.
   ``It looks like a jet,'' she added, saying she and he fiance are
looking seriously at minivans.
   The changes in design toward smoother cars is due in large part
to changes in manufacturing and engineering technology, along with
new materials.
   ``What's feasible to manufacturers continues to expand,'' said
analyst Charles Brady of Oppenheimer &amp; Co. of New York.
   ``Part of it is the (metal) stamping equipment,'' Glantz said.
``In the golden age of U.S. car design, we used thick steel with
very generous curves. It didn't fit very well.
   ``We went to simpler dies and less handwork and thinner steel and
that evolved into a boxier-looking car,'' he said. ``It's more
sophisticated engineering, you have to have much more precise dies.''
   Standing beside a maroon Audi 200 at the show were Kevin and Sue
Burt of Westland. ``The first thing that strikes me about the car is
the outside,'' Sue Burt said.
   ``It's the silhouette,'' she added, ``I don't like boxy cars.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
