<FIRST>r i AM-PLO-Embassies     01-07 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-PLO-Embassies,0502</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jordan Upgrades Palestinian Mission To Embassy Status</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMAL HALABY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Women sang and men cheered Saturday after
Jordan upgraded the PLO mission to an embassy and Yasser Arafat
hoisted the Palestinian flag over the building.
   China and Qatar also announced Saturday they would upgrade PLO
missions to embassies. The actions were seen as bolstering the PLO
chairman's Middle East peace initiative and demand for an
independent Palestinian state.
   Arafat waded through a crowd in Amman to raise the black, red,
white and green Palestinian banner in front of the Palestine
National Council headquarters that will apparently serve as the PLO
embassy in Amman. Prime Minister Zaid Rifai raised the Jordanian
banner next to the PLO flag.
   Eight states, including Saudi Arabia, Algeria, Bahrain, Iraq and
the United Arab Emirates, now have granted the PLO embassies.
   About 70 countries have recognized the Palestinian state
proclaimed in November by the Palestine National Council, the PLO's
parliament in exile. The boundaries of the state sought for
Palestinians have not been defined, but PLO officials say it would
roughly encompass the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Arafat told reporters Jordan's decision to upgrade the embassy
was ``true and strong support for the Palestinian cause, toward
retrieving Jerusalem so that we can raise these two flags on the
walls of Jerusalem once again.''
   He said no Palestinian ambassador to Jordan had been named.
   China's Xinhua news agency quoted a Foreign Ministry spokesman as
saying the PLO mission would be upgraded there to strengthen
friendly relations between the Chinese and Palestinian people.
   China, long a PLO supporter, is one of the five permanent members
of the U.N. Security Council. Arabs want the five to oversee
Arab-Israeli peace talks at an international conference.
   Qatar's Foreign Ministry said its decision to grant embassy
status to the PLO was due to the gulf state's desire to ``bolster
the legitimate national rights of the Palestinian people, especially
their right to self-determination and establishing their independent
state on their national soil.''
   The clandestine leadership of the 13-month-old Palestinian
uprising in the West Bank and Gaza Strip on Saturday issued a
communique calling on European countries to upgrade PLO offices in
their capitals and urging the United States to recognize the
Palestinian state.
   France has raised the PLO's status in Paris to that of ``general
delegation'' _ a step short of diplomatic recognition.
   Arafat met with King Hussein and Rifai on Saturday.
   Petra, the official Jordanian news agency, said Hussein expressed
``unlimited support for Mr. Arafat, the Palestinian brethren and
their just cause ... and support for the PLO in every way until the
Palestinian people achieve their goal'' of an independent homeland.
   Arafat said discussions covered ``ways of reaching a fair and
comprehensive peace'' with Israel and ``the importance of holding an
Arab summit to extend support to the Palestinian position and
advance the efforts of Arab unity.''
</TEXT>
