<FILEID>AP-NR-01-07-89 1649EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Mexico-SmogChecks     01-07 0669</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Smog Checks,0687</SECOND>
<HEAD>Long Waits for City's First Pollution Checks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS ANGELO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drivers trying to get their cars checked
before an anti-smog crackdown begins say they have waited in line
for hours and even days for the five-minute inspection.
   ``I've come four times so far,'' Jose Reyes said heatedly as he
got out of his battered white 1976 Rambler at one of the 32
governmen stations. ``Now I'm plain nervous.''
   The government and environmentalists say Mexico City's 3 million
vehicles account for 80 percent of its pollution, which regularly
exceeds maximum acceptable levels for ozone.
   Starting Monday, the city says cars visibly contaminating the air
will be stopped. Fines equal to 20 days' minimum wage, or about $76,
go into effect for violators Feb. 1, even if they have a sticker
certifying their cars are smog-free.
   To obtain a sticker, a driver must pass muster at one of the
inspection stations set up across the city. Inspections are free
until Feb. 1. After that, they'll cost about $3.80 _ the equivalent
of one day's mininum wage.
   Reyes said Thursday he had waited from just after midnight until
4 p.m. and had yet to get his inspection. He said he came in at 4
a.m. another day and found too many already in line.
   At a larger station, drivers said they had been in line only 30
minutes, but longer waits seemed to be the rule.
   At a parking lot in the south part of the city, 160 cars were in
line at 10 p.m. one night for the next day's scheduled 9 a.m.
opening, already more than the station could handle in a day.
   Miguel Angel Martinez said he was given a March 4 appointment at
the La Viga station in south-central Mexico City. ``I'd be in
violation by then,'' he said.
   A few drivers said some stations were issuing stickers in
exchange for bribes when cars failed the test.
   Adela Rodriguez said her car failed its first check, but the
inspector tried to sell her a sticker for $17.50. She offered him
$11, but he turned it down. Her car passed a later inspection.
   Eduardo Rodriguez, waiting in line with his '78 Dodge, said a
similar thing happened to a friend who's a chauffer and took some
company cars to a station. ``According to them, they weren't
properly tuned and they charged 20,000 pesos ($8.75) for the
sticker,'' Rodriguez said.
   Newspaper reports said places in line were selling for up to
20,000 pesos. Responding to complaints, Mayor Manuel Camacho Solis
on Friday urged citizens to report incidents of corruption to city
officials.
   Taking action against pollution is good, ``but I'd like to see
one of those buses come in here,'' Rodriguez said, watching a yellow
and brown city bus as it trailed a stream of black smoke from the
pipe on its roof.
   The testing so far is required only of private vehicles, which
account for 80 percent of Mexico City's vehicles. In 1987, private
cars carried only 18 percnt of 25 million daily passenger trips,
according to official figures. Subway, buses, trolleys, light trains
and taxis provided the other transportation.
   At the parking lot where Reyes was waiting, drivers had taken
matters into their own hands.
   Vilma Romero, a young volunteer, wrote license numbers on a
waiting list for the first available appointment time, eight days
later. She told drivers to come two days ahead to confirm the date
and the next day to pick up a number.
   The plan included leaving cars in line overnight to assure their
position. A guard was being paid about 45 cents apiece to watch
them, but some drivers said they were staying anyway.
   Heated arguments resulted when newcomers tried to jump the line.
   Reyes complained there was one mobile unit instead of two and it
didn't open on time.
   ``There's nothing of what they have promised,'' he said. ``The
people are obeying all the orders. Why don't they do their part?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
