<FILEID>AP-NR-01-07-89 1650EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Spain-Cugat     01-07 0228</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spain-Cugat,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>Band Leader Xavier Cugat in Stable Condition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BARCELONA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Band leader Xavier Cugat was responding
favorably Saturday to treatment for a lung inflammation but remained
in intensive care, a clinic spokeswoman said.
   The spokeswoman said the 89-year-old Spanish-born musician may be
moved to a regular room in Quiron Clinic in the next few days if he
continues to improve. His condition was stable Saturday, according
to the spokeswoman, who declined to be identified.
   Friends rushed Cugat to the clinic Friday for treatment of
``severe lung inflammation and high blood pressure,'' said his
physician, Dr. Jordi Rius.
   Cugat has suffered four heart attacks and a stroke since 1980. In
1987, he was twice treated for lung congestion.
   Born Jan. 1, 1900, in the northeastern Catalonian town of Gerona,
Cugat is credited with introducing tropical rhythms into American
dance music.
   When he was 4, he and his family left for Cuba, where he became a
violinist.
   After limited success in New York as a classical violinist, he
began playing Latin American rhythmic music with several bands
before organizing his own. Cugat became a star with his band in the
1930s playing Latin dance music in Los Angeles and later at the
Waldorf-Astoria Hotel in New York.
   In 1970 he turned over his band to Tito Puente, and a decade
later returned to live in Barcelona.
</TEXT>
