<FILEID>AP-NR-01-07-89 1709EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Armenia     01-07 0220</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Armenia,0226</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Foundation Stone Laid in Earthquake-Ravaged City</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One month after Armenia's devastating earthquake,
the foundation stone of a new apartment building was laid Saturday
in Leninakan to start reconstruction in the Armenian city.
   Authorities have pledged to rebuild within two years Leninakan
and other Armenian towns and villages leveled in the Dec. 7 quake
that killed tens of thousands of people.
   The quake destroyed about 200 apartment houses, factories and
buildings in Leninakan and left more than 500,000 people homeless.
   Leninakan, home to about 280,000 people before the disaster, will
be rebuilt with three- and four-story stone buildings that will be
more comfortable and earthquake-resistant than those that crumbled,
the official Soviet news agency Tass said.
   Many of the buildings destroyed in the quake were nine-story
apartment houses, and Prime Minister Nikolai I. Ryzhkov has said a
government commission will investigate whether building regulations
were violated by the erection of such structures in a seismically
active area.
   On Friday, the evening television news program ``Vremya'' showed
workers using explosives to demolish five-story apartment buildings
in Leninakan that had not been toppled by the tremor but were too
dangerous to inhabit.
   Workers on Saturday laid the first stone of an apartment building
in Leninakan that is to be part of a housing development, Tass said.
</TEXT>
