<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Drugs 1stLd-Writethru   01-07 0522</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Drugs, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0588,0533</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nineteen Drug Smugglers Hanged As Iranian Drug Crackdown Grows</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with two grafs to add reference to Iranian authorities
to lede and restore paragraph marker; picks up 2nd graf pvs: The official...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, CYPRUS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranian authorities hanged 19 narcotics
traffickers, some publicly, in an anti-drug drive in which more than
1,000 people were rounded up and dozens killed in shootouts, Iranian
news reports said Saturday.
   There are no official estimates available, but officials have
reported that drug abuse rose alarmingly during the 8-year war with
Iraq. Iran's crackdown began after the Aug. 20 cease-fire.
   The official Islamic Republic New Agency, monitored in Nicosia,
said 10 smugglers were convicted of running drug trafficking
networks, carrying illegal weapons, clashing with security forces,
and possessing a total of 167 pounds of heroin and 1,166 pounds of
opium.
   The agency said some were executed in Tehran's Qasr prison and
others publicly hanged in Bani-Hashem Square in the northwest
suburbs. It did not say when.
   Tehran Radio, also monitored in Nicosia, said nine other
convicted smugglers were hanged Friday and Saturday in other Iranian
cities.
   These included Mashhad in the northwest, near the Afghan border,
and Kerman and Zahedan in the southwest, a major smuggling route
from neighboring Pakistan.
   Iran television on Saturday night showed interviews with some of
the condemned men before their hangings.
   They were seated at what appeared to be school desks, and some
tried to hide their faces from the camera.
   One was asked if he had known the penalty for his crime was
death. ``I am an illiterate and didn't understand what was going on.
My father didn't have anything, so I committed this act,'' he said.
   Another man, whose name also was not given, said he was a truck
driver who was offered the equivalent of $12,000 to carry narcotics
from a provincial town to Tehran. ``I was tempted. It was purely
materialistic,'' he said.
   The radio said several of the men executed were kingpins in major
narcotics rings operating in the southwest, one of the main targets
of the crackdown.
   A statement by the office of the Islamic Revolutionary Prosecutor
in charge of the anti-narcotics campaign branded the executed men as
``the best examples of the corrupt on earth.''
   The executions were carried out in advance of a tough new law
that takes effect Jan. 21 under which the death sentence is
mandatory for anyone caught carrying 30 grams (just more than 1
ounce) of heroin, morphine, codeine or methadone or smuggling more
than 11 pounds of any narcotic.
   Any person who is found responsible for addicting another faces a
minimum sentence of 20 years imprisonment.
   The Expediency Council, set up by revolutionary leader Ayatollah
Ruhollah Khomeini in February to speed up legislation snarled in
Tehran's bureaucratic machine, announced the new law Dec. 5.
   In addition to the Persian Gulf War, other likely factors in the
rise in drug smuggling and opium growing include a ban on alcohol,
worsening unemployment and the breakdown of political control in the
first years of the Islamic revolution.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890107-0124 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-07-89 1818EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-TeenStarved     01-07 0666</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Teen Starved,0686</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teen-Age Starving Victim Buried; Charged Parents Remain Hospitalized</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Stands for Kingston, Pa.,-datelined item on AM-News Advisory</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARVERTON, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 14-year-old boy who died of starvation
despite his parents having nearly $4,000 in savings was buried
Saturday before a handful of strangers.
   Eric Cottam's family was unable to attend. They were in hospital
beds, under treatment for malnutrition.
   His parents, Larry and Leona Cottam, have been charged with
criminal homicide in the death. The boy died Tuesday night after the
family hadn't eaten for 42 days, Larry Cottam told police.
   Larry Cottam, 39, said he didn't use $3,775 in cash, bonds and
bank accounts to buy food because it was a tithe belonging to God,
according to an affidavit filed by state police. Cottam, a former
Seventh-day Adventist preacher, believed God would provide for his
reclusive family, acquaintances said.
   The private, 10-minute graveside service was attended by nine
people, said Hubert Morgan, a Seventh-day Adventist pastor who
conducted the service. He said his wife, a local funeral director
and six pallbearers also attended and none of them knew the boy. The
church paid for the boy's burial, he said.
   ``It's tragic that he was cut short in life _ that he didn't get
to enjoy a full life,'' Morgan said. He said Larry Cottam told him
he wanted the service private and requested that relatives in
California not be present; Morgan said he didn't know how to contact
them.
   The time and the location of the service were kept secret to try
to keep away the media and others who wished to attend.
   ``A lot of members (of the congregation) wanted to go. Not out of
curiosity, out of sympathy,'' Morgan said in a telephone interview.
   A spokesman at Geisinger Wyoming Valley Medical
Center-Wilkes-Barre said Larry Cottam was in fair condition and
Leona Cottam was in serious condition. Their daughter, Laura, 12,
was listed in serious condition at Mercy Hospital.
   Eric, whose dream was to become a meteorologist, was 5-foot-10
and weighed 69 pounds when he died, 80 pounds less than normal,
Luzerne County Coroner George E. Hudock Jr. said.
   His brief life was dominated by his family, neighbors and school
officials said.
   He and Laura scored extremely well on standardized tests, but
since 1985 they were taught at home by their mother, Crestwood
School District officials said.
   Cottam, who was fired in March from his job as a truck driver,
said his savings represented 10 percent of his total earnings,
according to the affidavit. Tithes, which are usually 10 percent,
are used to pay the local pastor and for evangelical work, said
Frank Kowalski, first elder at the Seventh-day Adventist church in
Slocum, four miles from the Cottam's home.
   Kowalski said the Cottams hadn't paid a tithe to the local church
since they returned to the area in 1985. Morgan said the Cottams
hadn't attended his church in Slocum in his 14 months as pastor.
   In 1983, Cottam became an intern pastor, ministering to Slocum
and three other nearby churches with a total congregation of about
250. He was stripped of his license to preach in 1985 because of
strained relations with the congregations.
   Seventh-day Adventists are fundamentally evangelical and take the
Bible as their sole rule of faith and practice.
   ``I think they (the Cottams) took the Lord and tested him to the
extreme,'' said Kowalski, a building contractor from nearby Dorrance.
   Cottam told a reporter Wednesday night he blamed himself, not
God, for his son's death.
   He and his wife were arraigned separately Thursday night at Mercy
Hospital.
   No bail was set, and a preliminary hearing was scheduled for
Friday. In addition to criminal homicide, they face two counts each
of recklessly endangering another person and endangering the welfare
of children.
   Death is the maximum sentence for criminal homicide.
   Joseph Loftus-Vergari, executive director of the Luzerne County
Children and Youth Services, said his agency was investigating
whether the Cottams are able to properly care for their daughter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
