<FIRST>r i AM-Sudan-Strikes     01-07 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan-Strikes,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>Water Works Idled by Strikes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government water utility workers went on
strike Saturday, threatening water shortages for at least 1 million
people in the capital and in western Sudan.
   Five unions at the official Sudan News Agency, representing
editorial and other workers, also began a seven-day strike.
   The latest strikes follow four days of violent street
demonstrations and a general strike in late December against steep
price increases. The protests ended after the financially strapped
government rolled back prices.
   Workers at the the Sudanese Rural Waters Corp. demanded better
working conditions and wage increases for employees.
   The strike affected 245 water stations in Khartoum, most of them
in the industrial northern area, and further aggravated water
shortages suffered by residents in the mainly desert regions of
Darfur and Kordofan in the west.
   Union leaders representing workers at the Sudan News Agency met
with Abdallah Mohamed Ahmed, the culture and information minister,
but failed to head off the walkout. The unions voiced opposition to
deteriorating professional standards and an alleged lack of
leadership.
   In the past few months, powerful trade and professional unions
have orchestrated strikes by teachers, communication technicians,
Information Ministry employees and civil aviation technicians and
air controllers.
   The government says the unrest at the end of last month left one
person dead and 26 injured, but Western sources say at least four
died and more than 26 were hurt.
   The protests and general strike prompted Prime Minister Sadek
Mahdi's Cabinet on Dec. 29 to revoke commodity price increases of up
to 500 percent and a 15 percent across-the-board sales tax. It also
made retroactive to July 1 instead of Dec. 1, salary increases of 50
percent to 300 percent decreed a week before for all public and
private employees.
   Since then, the government has been discussing with trade and
professional unions ways to finance the salary increases.
</TEXT>
