<FIRST>r i AM-AssassinationProbe     01-07 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Assassination Probe,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chilean Prosecutor Approves U.S. Request to Question Former Officials</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prosecutor approved a U.S. request to
question seven former government officials about the 1976
assassination in Washington of a retired Chilean minister, news
reports said Saturday.
   However, the ruling Thursday by prosecutor Rene Pica must be
upheld by a six-member panel of the Supreme Court, which is to meet
Monday, local newspapers said. The panel includes two justices who
have in the past opposed U.S. extradition requests in the case.
   Orlando Letelier and an American aid, Ronnie Moffit, were killed
on Sept. 21, 1976, by a bomb that blew up Letelier's car as he drove
along Embassy Row in Washington.
   Letelier was an ambassador to Washington and later foreign
minister in the leftist government of President Salvador Allende.
Letelier was an avowed foe of Augusto Pinochet, who overthrew the
government in a 1973 coup that left Allende dead.
   Investigators believe that the seven former Chilean officials may
have information about what they describe as a plot by Chilean
intelligence agents to kill Letelier and a later cover-up, according
to papers filed in U.S. District Court in Washington.
   
   The U.S. request, signed by U.S. District Judge Barrington
Parker, was filed Dec. 28 by the U.S. Justice Department through the
Chilean Foreign Ministry.
   Parker wants to question Gen. Odlanier Mena, former head of the
secret police; Miguel Schweitzer, former foreign minister; air force
Gen. Enrique Montero, former interior minister; Jose Miguel Barros,
Manuel Trucco and Jorge Cauas, all former Chilean ambassadors to
Washington; and Tomas Amenabar, who was at the time a charge
d'affaires in the Chilean Embassy. Cauas was later appointed finance
minister.
   Barros is now a prominent foe of Pinochet's government.
   A former Chilean army major, Armando Fernandez Larios, who left
Chile and surrendered to U.S. authorities in 1987, provided U.S.
investigators with information that led to the request, according to
U.S. court papers.
   Fernandez and two other high-ranking Chilean army officers were
indicted in the 1970s in the United States in connection with the
assassination. However, the Chilean Supreme Court turned down a
request for their extradition.
</TEXT>
