<HEAD>Precede WASHINGTON</HEAD>
<HEAD>Barry Associate Denies Drug Use in Interview</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout with more details, quotes</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Mayor Barry, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE AMALIE, St. Thomas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The central figure in two
federal inquiries involving Washington, D.C., Mayor Marion Barry Jr.
has denied using drugs with the mayor, a newspaper reported Saturday.
   The Virgin Islands Daily News also quoted Charles Lewis as
defending his role in a heavily-criticized joint venture between the
governments of the District of Columbia and the Virgin Islands.
   Lewis, a former District of Columbia and Virgin Islands
government official, was the target of a police drug effort on Dec.
22 after a maid at his Washington hotel complained he had offered
her drugs in exchange for sex. An undercover attempt to buy drugs
from Lewis that day was called off after Barry showed up at Lewis'
room.
   However, Lewis denied offering drugs to the hotel maid in
exchange for sex, the newspaper said. He was quoted as saying that a
misunderstanding arose when he was looking for writing paper to
complete a job application.
   ``There was a service tray with writing paper on it, and I asked
the housekeeper, in the presence of two maintenance men, in Spanish,
if I could have the paper.
   ``When I got the paper off the tray, a light piece of plastic _
probably a used disposable shower cap _ fell off the tray, and I
picked it up to give to the housekeeper,'' Lewis told the Daily News.
   ``She started acting funny,'' he was quoted as saying.
   Lewis said Barry was in his room later to help him find a job.
   Lewis, who had not spoken publicly about the incident until the
press account Saturday, remains at an undisclosed location. His
version of the story differs little from that of Barry, who said he
was simply visiting an old friend at the hotel.
   Barry has denied using drugs with Lewis and said he was unaware
Lewis was under police investigation.
   Federal investigators are trying to determine whether Barry
thwarted a separate police investigation into the matter, why he was
visiting Lewis at the hotel, and whether Lewis was using or selling
drugs.
   Barry has denied interfering with the city's drug investigation.
   The U.S. attorney for the District of Columbia, Jay B. Stephens,
has expanded his inquiry to include the city's involvement in a
$260,000 joint venture between the city and Virgin Islands
government to upgrade the islands' personnel system.
   Lewis headed the project but was fired in April after Virgin
Islands officials became concerned about cost overruns. Stephens is
trying to find out whether city officials working on the project
charged personal items and expenses to their account with the Virgin
Islands government.
   In his Daily News interview, Lewis said the reason hotel costs
for the personnel project were so high was because Virgin Islands
Gov. Alexander Farrelly was slow with paperwork, which put the
project into the busy season when rates are higher.
   The Daily News quoted Farrelly as saying Friday that he fired
Lewis because he was ``dissatisfied with the pace of the
activities'' and felt some of the consultants' expenditures
``warranted criminal investigation.''
</TEXT>
