<FILEID>AP-NR-01-07-89 2040EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Latvia     01-07 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Latvia,0478</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Forms Apparently To Counter Activists; Party Chief Warns Ethnic
Split</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group formed Saturday appears to challenge local
activists seeking autonomy in the Baltic republic of Latvia, where
the Communist Party chief says independent organizations are causing
ethnic divisions.
   The new Latvian organization, the Inter-National Front, held its
organizing congress in Riga, the Latvian capital. Tass, the official
Soviet news agency, said preliminary data indicate the group is
supported by 300,000 of the republic's 2.6 million inhabitants.
   ``The new mass organization proclaimed its main goal to promote
and further extend the perestroika reform program,'' Tass said,
referring to the campaign for economic and social change mounted by
Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   However, Latvian nationalists and activists say the group is
dominated by ethnic Russians and is intended to be a counterweight
to the Latvian People's Front, which is seeking greater autonomy for
the Baltic republic from Moscow.
   ``They are anti-perestroika,'' said Boris Sokolov, a Riga-based
member of the Democratic Union, an independent group seeking to
challenge the political monopoly of the Communist Party.
   At a Thursday meeting of the Latvian party's Central Committee,
the republic's party chief, Janis Vagris, seemed to distance himself
both from the People's Front and the Inter-National Front.
   According to state-run Radio Moscow, Vagris said ``various public
organizations had emerged lately in the republic, such as the
People's Front, where ethnic Latvians constitute a majority, and the
Inter-Nationalist Front, made up mostly of people of other
nationalities living in the republic.''
   The existence of such groups ``has been causing ethnic
stratification in Latvia,'' he said.
   ``Both movements have some extremist-minded elements,'' Vagris
was quoted as saying. ``Both also involve members of the Communist
Party, which means that there is also stratification within the
party.''
   He said that was ``impermissible'' and called on the
organizations to ``lose no time in renouncing confrontation and join
forces instead in promoting the process of perestroika,'' Radio
Moscow said.
   Despite Vagris' criticisms, one of the founders of the
Inter-National Front said its members were seeking ethnic harmony
but indicated the group will seek to remain outside party control.
   ``When creating the Inter-National Front, we proceeded from the
fact that the interests of the working people of various
nationalities largely coincided, while differences between them were
not antagonistic,'' Tass quoted Anatoly Belaichuk as telling the
Saturday congress.
   ``It means we can jointly work for the victory of perestroika
initiated by our Communist Party,'' said Belaichuk, a rector at the
Riga Institute of Civil Aviation Engineering.
   Ethnic Latvians make up 54 percent of Latvia's population,
according to the most recent official data, obtained in the 1979
Soviet census. Ethnic Russians total 33 percent of Latvia's
population, while 5 percent are Ukrainians, 3 percent Byelorussians
and 3 percent ethnic Poles.
</TEXT>
