<FIRST>r i AM-Jamaica-Arms     01-07 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jamaica-Arms,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jamaica Deports Alleged Drug Dealers in $8 Million Arms-Smuggling
Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities are deporting eight
foreigners accused of posing as Colombian military officials to ship
$8 million worth of weapons through Jamaica to leftist rebels in
Colombia, an official said Saturday.
   National Security Minister Errol Anderson of Jamaica, who made
the announcement, did not identify the men. However, he said three
were Colombian, four Panamanian, and one British.
   He said the men were involved in ``narco-terrorism and the
Medellin cartel,'' referring to a leading Colombian drug-trafficking
group.
   ``In questioning the conspirators, it was learned that the arms
were destined for a leftist Colombian insurgent group called the
Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia,'' he said. ``This group is
in league with and financed by Colombian cocaine traffickers.''
   The rebel group, one of several opposed to the Colombian
government, has made known through an intermediary that it would
like to open peace talks with the government.
   Anderson said the weapons arrived on this Caribbean island
shortly before Christmas via a Panamanian-registered freighter.
   He said Colombian officials were invited to Jamaica on Thursday
to witness the opening of the crates, which contained machine guns,
assault rifles, mortars and hand guns. The Colombian officials
returned with the weapons and the three detained Colombians on
Friday, he said.
   Anderson said the Panamanians and Briton were to be deported
Saturday. He said two of the Panamanians were pilots who were to fly
the weapons from Jamaica to Colombia.
   The official said the weapons were paid for by cocaine sent to
Europe. He said the arms came from West Germany, where they were
made by the firm Heckler and Koch.
</TEXT>
