<FIRST>r a AM-People-Candy     01-07 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Candy,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Comedian John Candy Plays Disc Jockey For a New Syndicated Radio
Show</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: `Valri Bromfield' in 5th graf is cq</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Southern California radio listeners may be
startled Sunday morning to hear traffic reports delivered by
Commander Wes Steel, who surveys road conditions in a B-52 bomber
and shoots at stalled cars.
   The maniacal traffic reporter is the creation of comedian John
Candy and a radio troupe whose new syndicated comedy show, ``Radio
Kandy,'' is a parody of popular radio.
   The weekly two-hour show, featuring Candy as a disc jockey, is
scheduled to be heard at 8 a.m. Sundays on KNX-FM and eventually
over 225 radio stations nationwide. It is distributed by the
Transtar Radio Network.
   Candy first gained fame on ``Second City TV,'' (``SCTV'') a
now-defunct show about a fictional television station. From there
Candy moved to the big screen, starring in such movies as
``Splash,'' ``Planes, Trains and Automobiles,'' and ``Little Shop of
Horrors.''
   Joining Candy on the show will be ``SCTV'' alumni Joe Flaherty,
Valri Bromfield and Ira Miller. Candy said many ``SCTV'' characters
will be reprised for radio, but it will not be a ``Second City
Radio.''
   ``I don't know what it is going to be yet; we'll see what works.
That is how `SCTV' evolved,'' he said.
   Candy said he is not in danger of becoming a so-called ``shock
radio'' DJ.
   ``It's like how gross can you get? How low can you go? Who can
you wake up and disturb? Whose life can you wreck today? And when
you finally meet these people, they are really quite the opposite,''
he said.
   ``We will give a nice mixture of music and humor,'' Candy said.
``It won't beat you over the head.''
</TEXT>
