<HEAD>About 100 Anti-Abortion Protesters Arrested in Worcester</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 1st graf and 7th graf, `Coakley said' to UPDATE with final
count of protesters arrested, which police say is 92 sted more than 100.
Darroline is cq in 4th graf.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WORCESTER, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested nearly 100 anti-abortion
protesters Saturday who sang Christmas carols while blocking
doorways and jamming elevators at an abortion clinic, officials said.
   Police dragged and carried away the protesters, who filled
hallways of a busy office building and prevented 15 women from
entering the Planned Parenthood League of Massachusetts clinic,
officials said.
   Four of the protesters fastened heavy-duty bicycle locks around
their necks, interweaving the locks and throwing away the keys.
   ``It just makes it take longer (to clear the entrance),''
explained protester Darroline Firlit. ``It takes them a long time to
try a hacksaw and figure out that it won't work and then get the
Fire Department and send for a locksmith.''
   ``It only takes three minutes to kill a baby. So every three
minutes we save is another life.''
   Another group of 50 to 75 anti-abortion protesters, also members
of the national anti-abortion group Operation Rescue, picketed
peacefully outside the downtown building, said Deputy Police Chief
John Coakley.
   Police said 92 protesters who blocked entrances to the clinic and
refused to move were arrested, charged with trespassing and released
on their own recognizance pending arraignment Tuesday.
   The protest was one in a series of anti-abortion demonstrations
in Massachusetts in recent months, including one Dec. 31 in which
about 75 members of Operation Rescue's Boston chapter were arrested.
   The clinic opened three hours late, at 11 a.m., after all the
protesters were removed, and all but one of 15 patients who had
abortion appointments in the morning waited for the protesters to be
hauled away rather than reschedule the procedure, clinic officials
said.
   About 50 members of the Boston chapter of the National
Organization for Women staged a counter-protest outside the building.
   ``It would be unheard-of to block a voting booth,'' said Ellen
Convisser, president of the Boston NOW chapter. ``And it should be
equally underheard-of to block my constitutional right to enter an
abortion clinic.''
</TEXT>
