<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Raisa     01-07 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Raisa,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Group Picks Candidates _ But Not Raisa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet cultural group picked five candidates
Saturday to sit on a new national political body, but the
organization's best-known member, Raisa Gorbachev, was conspicuously
absent from the list.
   It is not known if the wife of Soviet President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev, who attended the meeting according to state-run
television, presented herself as a candidate to represent the Soviet
Culture Fund. She helped create the organization in 1986.
   If so, her failure to achieve election could be a clear rebuff to
her husband. However, the wives of Kremlin leaders do not usually
engage in political or Communist Party business.
   Excerpts of Saturday's meeting in Moscow were shown on the
Saturday evening television news show ``Vremya.''
   The program said the Soviet Culture Fund was entitled to send
five representatives to the Council of People's Deputies. The
council is a new 2,250-member body that will chose members of the
national Supreme Soviet legislature and elect the Soviet president,
the post now held by Gorbachev.
   The five chosen included Dmitri Likhachev, a top member of the
literature and language department of the Soviet Academy of
Sciences; and Daniel Granin, a prominent Leningrad author, Vremya
said.
   The 750 candidates to the Council of People's Deputies from
public organizations like the Culture Fund will be submitted to the
organizations' congresses and conferences in March for a vote. In
addition, 1,500 deputies will be elected to represent territorial
divisions and the 15 constituent Soviet republics.
   The Culture Fund is an umbrella group for the arts that tries to
involve more Soviets in cultural pursuits, provide financial support
and help young artists gain public recognition.
   Mrs. Gorbachev, a former philosophy teacher, arouses strong
passions among Soviets. Some admire what they view as her sense of
style, while others condemn her for extravagant taste in clothes and
public assertiveness.
</TEXT>
