<FIRST>r a AM-HotHouse     01-07 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hot House,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Radioactive House Cleanup To Cost $9.5 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LANSDOWNE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The cleanup of a radioactive house
contaminated by a professor processing radium in the basement will
cost $9.5 million and involve digging up neighbors' lawns and
possibly garages, federal officials say.
   It is the second major price increase for the project, which is
being financed by the federal Superfund cleanup program.
   In 1984, the cleanup cost was estimated at $2 million. Last
August, as the cleanup began, officials estimated the cost at $7.5
million.
   ``A lot of the areas we are excavating turned out to be
contaminated,'' Nanci L. Sinclair, a spokeswoman for the U.S.
Environmental Protection Agency, said Friday. ``In some areas we
went down seven to nine feet'' before finding clean soil.
   Officials found that portions of the lawns of four surrounding
homes were radioactive.
   Since August, contractors have been pulling apart the house and
its lawn. The house was contaminated in the 1930s and 1940s by a
University of Pennsylvania professor.
   By November, contractors had torn down the entire house and
shipped it to a special dump site in Utah. Only the lawn remained,
but that has proven to be much more radioactive than previously
thought, Sinclair said.
   Instead of the 1,000 tons of soil contractors expected to remove,
they will cart off 2,200 tons to the Utah dump, Sinclair said.
   Victor J. Janosik, EPA project manager, said he expects the
cleanup to be completed by May or June.
   ``I've never seen the price of these things go down,'' he said.
</TEXT>
