<FIRST>u a AM-ChurchClosings     01-07 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Church Closings,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Detroit Parishes Get Word of Closings, Some Spared</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of at least a dozen Roman Catholic
inner-city churches were told Saturday that their parishes will
close by summer, while others rejoiced upon learning they won't have
to sit in someone else's pew.
   The plan first announced in September by the Archdiocese of
Detroit called for closing or merging 48 parishes, the most
widespread move of its kind in U.S. Catholic history. Officials
cited declining membership, a shortage of priests and the increasing
cost of supporting the parishes.
   But according to announcements at services Saturday, three
parishes targeted for closing would be kept open; two would be
merged with other churches; and two would remain open until their
pastors retired.
   At least 18 other parishes mentioned in the original list were
designated as ``questionably viable.'' Each was given six months to
a year to coduct a self-study about its future with the assistance
of archdiocesan leaders, parishioners were told Saturday.
   Nearly two dozen other parishes that did not have Saturday Masses
were to learn their fates Sunday.
   Cardinal Edmund Szoka disclosed his final decisions to pastors in
private meetings last week, giving them permission to release the
information during weekend services. A formal announcement by Szoka
was scheduled for Sunday afternoon.
   Szoka has defended the closings as necessary to wipe out a
``plantation mentality'' in which white pastors and lay people run
churches attended mostly by blacks because of white flight to the
suburbs. But his home has been picketed by both black and white
parishioners in the nation's sixth-largest city.
   At St. Theresa of Avila Parish, which will merge with another
parish, the Rev. Robert Morand said he was asked to keep the news a
secret until his Saturday afternoon Mass.
   ``The idea is that he (Szoka) sticks a dagger in you and says,
`Don't tell anybody it's there until Saturday,''' Morand said. ``I
really believe he sincerely thinks he's right. But he says he's
doing God's will. He has said that often, and I resent it very much.
   ``It isn't God's will. It's a travesty.''
   Attitudes were upbeat, however, at parishes spared closing.
   ``That's wonderful news. What a wonderful way to begin the new
year,'' said the Rev. John Quinn of St. Luke's parish on the city's
west side, whose 70 parishioners learned Saturday their church
earned a one-year reprieve.
   ``We are open and here to do the Lord's work.''
</TEXT>
