<DOCNO> AP890107-0156 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-01-07-89 0246EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:Heym Adv12   01-07 0938</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Heym, Adv 12,0962</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv12</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thu AMs, Jan 12 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Offending the Censors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than three decades after renouncing his U.S
citizenship and returning to East Germany, novelist Stefan Heym's
American experience continues to infuse his writing and offend his
nation's censors.
   ``From my experience in America I learned to fight back and speak
up,'' the 75-year-old writer said in a recent interview at his East
Berlin home. ``I learned that you don't have to take things lying
down.''
   Heym's critical views have resulted in a ban of almost all of his
later works in his homeland, and he has struggled for more than two
decades with East German censors. His latest book, a voluminous
memoir titled ``Nachruf'' (``Obituary''), has only been published in
West Germany.
   Because of his prominence, East German officials allow him to
publish his books in the West and to accept hard currency royalty
payments.
   He is also permitted to travel freely to the West, a privilege
enjoyed only by a select few of the nation's authors, artists and
trusted party officials.
   ``I'm just too well known now for them to hurt me,'' Heym said,
adding that he has won the grudging respect of party foes in his
clashes with them over the years.
   His first novel, ``Hostages,'' was written in English and
published in the United States in 1942. A movie based on the novel
was released a year later. While his early work received
considerable critical acclaim, most of his novels are no longer in
print in the United States.
   Heym returned to East Germany in the early 1950s after becoming
disillusioned with the advent of the McCarthy era and the American
involvement in the Korean War.
   ``I loved the United States,'' he said.
   ``It was the time of Roosevelt and the New Deal. Then came
McCarthy and it all changed,'' Heym said, referring to
anti-communist hysteria sparked by Sen. Joseph McCarthy that left
hundreds of creative artists blacklisted.
   Heym, the son of a Jewish merchant, was forced to flee Germany in
1933 after the Nazis took power. He traveled first to Prague, where
he worked as a journalist for a variety of left-wing publications.
It was there that the young writer abandoned his given name of
Helmut Flieg and created the pseudonym Stefan Heym in order to
secretly inform his family in Chemnitz (now Karl-Marx-Stadt) that he
had arrived safely in Czechoslovakia.
   In 1935, he received a scholarship from a New York-based Jewish
organization and enrolled at the University of Chicago.
   He stayed on in the United States, writing and editing
anti-fascist newspapers in New York as Adolf Hitler's war engulfed
more and more of Europe. He later served in the U.S. Army in a
special psychological warfare unit in Europe charged with the task
of demoralizing the will of German troops to fight.
   Heym published four novels in the United States before returning
to East Germany, which he said he believed at the time was the
Germany ``where there was the most hope that something new and
better could be forged.''
   The respected Hamburg-based weekly newspaper Die Zeit, however,
in a review of ``Nachruf,'' suggested that other, opportunistic
considerations were also a factor in his decision to return to East
Germany.
   ``The reasons for Heym's return appear well-known _ McCarthyism
and the Korean War,'' Die Zeit said. ``But another factor played a
role _ a lack of artistic success in America. Then came the
fortuituous invitation to return. In this he saw a chance for a new
professional beginning.''
   Heym said that after a brief, uncritical love affair with the
fledgling communist state, he turned more and more to an analysis of
social and political problems that brought a series of stern rebukes
from the party's leadership, who rejected his calls for ``discussion
without taboos.''
   Official dissatisfication over the course of his writing prompted
former East German leader Walter Ulbricht to mockingly refer to Heym
as ``an American writer with an East German passport.''
   He still frequently writes passages in English first because
``its precision and economy demands clearer thinking than cloudy
German.''
   Heym devotes a considerable part of his best-selling ``Nachruf''
to detailing his battle with East German censors and his fight to
break free of ideological limits imposed on his works.
   But it is also a compelling chronicle of Hitler's rise to power
and the fate of a generation uprooted and decimated by war.
   ``This was the most difficult book I have ever written,'' he
said. ``It was an effort at self-accounting on a scale I had never
attempted before.''
   Heym said he used the third person in the memoir as a literary
device in an effort to create a critical distance to his own life.
He evokes a refined sense of history and self-irony in retelling his
own often contradictory political development and the many macabre
and brutal events that shaped the century.
   The narrative distance also helped him come to terms with the
loss of relatives murdered by the Nazis. Three of Heym's five aunts
were murdered in Nazi death camps, along with a daughter he never
knew. Many of his friends died in concentration camps or were
executed for resistance efforts.
   Heym said he hoped that ``Nachruf'' would someday be approved for
publication in East Germany, although he predicted that it would not
happen anytime soon. The government has begun to gradually soften
its stand on several of his earlier books, approving the publication
of two novels over the next two years.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thu AMs, Jan. 12</NOTE>
</DOC>
