<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:1989Movies Adv09   01-07 0740</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: 1989 Movies, Adv 09,0758</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv09</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon AMs, Jan 9 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>A Guarded But Hopeful Movie Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After a rip-roaring 1988, the film industry
anticipates _ with wary optimism _ a new season that will bring such
surefire moneymakers as Indiana Jones and the ``Star Trek'' gang, as
well as the return of ``The Fly'' and those hilarious folks of
``Police Academy.''
   If box-office hopes are somewhat guarded, that's because the
movie menu is leaner than usual. Last year's 22-week writers' strike
has finally been evidenced in fewer releases for the pre-summer
season, traditionally a slow period. The fall stepup in production
assures that the rest of the year will bring a plentiful supply.
   A cautious note is supplied by Daily Variety's Art Murphy. After
noting that the 1988 domestic (U.S. and Canada) gross would amount
to a record $4.4 billion, he added a historical note: Previous
industry booms have lasted 30 to 42 months, followed by an average
18 months of recession. The current prosperity began in June 1986.
Hence a downturn is due, according to business cycles.
   The most awaited film event of 1989 is Paramount's ``Indiana
Jones and the Last Crusade,'' coming on May 24. The two previous
adventures starring Harrison Ford rank among the top 10 moneymakers
of all time. The new collaboration of Steven Spielberg and George
Lucas has the added allure of Sean Connery as Indiana's father, Dr.
Henry Jones.
   Paramount plans a one-two punch that might help restore its
position as the top-grossing releasing company, the crown now held
by Disney's Buena Vista. June will bring ``Star Trek V: The Final
Frontier,'' directed by Captain Kirk himself, William Shatner.
   Buena Vista hopes to hold its position with a varied program. The
dramatic ``Beaches,'' with Bette Midler and Barbara Hershey as
longtime friends, goes into national release this month. On the
lighter side are two crime-oriented comedies, ``Three Fugitives''
with Nick Nolte and Martin Short; ``Bank Job'' with Corbin Bernsen,
Reuben Blades and Lou Diamond Phillips; plus a re-release of ``The
Rescuers.''
   Episodic films are rarely proved successful, but Disney is trying
again with ``New York Stories,'' a trilogy with films by Woody
Allen, Francis Coppola and Martin Scorsese.
   Comedies have dominated the year-end product, and they will be in
big supply this year. They include:
   _ ``Major League,'' a story of baseball misfits with Tom
Berenger, Charlie Sheen and Corbin Bernsen.
   _ ``Let It Ride,'' Richard Dreyfuss as a gambler trying to get
rich against all odds.
   _ ``Cousins,'' Ted Danson and Isabella Rossellini in an
Americanized ``Cousin Cousine.''
   _ ``The Experts,'' John Travolta and Ayre Gross involved in a
Soviet plot in deepest Nebraska.
   _ ``The 'Burbs,'' Tom Hanks, Carrie Fisher and Bruce Dern in a
suburban comedy.
   _ ``Se You in the Morning,'' Farrah Fawcett and Jeff Bridges in a
story of divorce and remarriage.
   _ ``Bert Rigby, You're a Fool,'' Carl Reiner directs a comedy
with music. Robert Lindsay, the Broadway sensation in ``Me and My
Girl,'' stars.
   _ ``Penn and Teller Get Killed,'' the two comedians in a film
directed by Arthur Penn.
   _ ``Who's Harry Crumb?'' John Candy as a bumbling detective.
   _ ``Chances Are,'' a supernatural comedy with Cybill Shepherd,
Robert Downey Jr., Ryan O'Neal and Mary Stuart Masterson.
   _ ``Skin Deep,'' John Ritter as a hard-drinking author with
writer's block.
   Adventure and horror also figure in the pre-summer schedule.
Among the offerings: ``Farewell to the King,'' Nick Nolte in a World
War II story laid in Borneo; ``Pink Cadillac,'' Clint Eastwood as a
fugitive hunter (not Dirty Harry); ``Dead Bang,'' Don Johnson as an
L.A. cop tracking a killer across the country; ``Millenium,'' Kris
Kristofferson and Cheryl Ladd in a time warp caused by a jetliner
collision; ``The Witches,'' Anjelica Huston and Mai Zetterling
trying to turn the children of England into mice; ``Speed Zone,''
Brooke Shields, John Candy, Tim Matheson and a large cast in a
cross-country auto race.
   Tri-Star Pictures is offering a few musicals in the coming
months: ``Tap,'' Gregory Hines as a tap dancer returning home from
prison; ``Sing,'' a young cast in a song-and-dance competition in
Brooklyn high schools.
   Aside from the newcomers, such holiday holdovers as ``Rain Man,''
``Twins,'' ``The Naked Gun'' and ``Working Girl'' can be expected to
remain profitable well into the new year.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon Ams, Jan. 9</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
