<FIRST>a f BC-WeeklyBonds Adv07-08   01-07 0654</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Weekly Bonds, Adv 07-08,0688</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv 07</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv 08</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions Jan. 7-8</HEAD>
<HEAD>Caution Prevails In First Week Of Bond Trading</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bond traders rang in the new year the same way
they rang out the old _ with worries about inflation, the dollar and
the stubborn trade and federal budget deficits lingering like a bad
hangover.
   ``I think it's going to be a difficult year for the financial
markets,'' said Robert A. Brusca, chief financial economist for
Nikko Securities Co. International.
   He and a number of other economists are predicting that interest
rates will head higher in the first half of 1989 due to the overall
strength of the economy, although some experts are slightly more
optimistic about the near-term.
   ``The Fed may do a little snugging here and there, but no major
moves are needed,'' Brusca said. ``I think they tend to feel that
interest rates are already high enough.''
   Short-term rates, in particular, rose sharply in 1988, reflecting
the Federal Reserve's desire beginning last March to tighten credit
to prevent inflation from heating up. Longer-term rates remained
fairly stable, though.
   That same trend continued into the first week of trading in 1989,
causing a more pronounced inversion of the so-called yield curve,
which illustrates the difference between short- and long rates and
normally slopes upward.
   ``We're seeing a flatter yield curve overall,'' said Mitchell
Held, chief economist for Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co.
   For instance, the yield on the three-month Treasury bill has
risen 0.21 percentage points to 8.52 percent since the end of last
year, while the yield on the 30-year bond moved up only 0.08
percentage points to 9.06 percent.
   Part of the reason for the rise in short-term rates so far this
year is that fact that the federal funds rate, the interest banks
charge each other on overnight loans, has remained relatively high.
   Some analysts say the rise in the fed funds rate represents
merely a carryover of yearend corporate demand for money, but others
say the Fed could do more to keep a healthy dose of reserves in the
banking system.
   ``There are a lot of things the Fed could have said and done ...
and didn't,'' said Held.
   Still, interest rates and bond prices remained relatively stable
in the first week of 1989 trading, mainly because of the dollar's
surprising strength in foreign exchange. Shearson Lehman Hutton
Inc.'s Treasury Bond Index, which measures the price of all
outstanding Treasuries, rose marginally since the end of last year.
   ``This strength in the dollar is giving us some breathing room in
the year,'' said Brusca.
   The U.S. downing of two Libyan jets in the Mediterranean this
past week had helped push up the currency, since the dollar is often
considered a safe haven amid international tension.
   The dollar still remains a major concern among bond traders this
year, analysts say, since the market sentiment toward it remains
fairly bearish. A weak currency makes dollar-denominated bonds less
attractive to foreigners and often sparks higher inflation, which
erodes the value of fixed-income securities.
   Besides the lingering trade and budget deficits, which helped
spark the 1987 stock market crash, bond traders this year remainly
acutely worried about inflation as evidence points to a generally
strong economy.
   ``You're not going to see inflation falling,'' said Brusca, who
noted that the businesses are still using their plants and equipment
to near capacity.
   One bit of positive news this past week, however, came from the
December unemployment data. Although the jobless rate last month
fell to 5.3 percent, dropping back to a 14-year low, many economists
noted that average annual earnings remained unchanged for a third
consecutive month and that the average factory work week declined.
   ``That isn't symptomatic of a booming economy,'' said William V.
Sullivan, an economist with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Jan. 7-8</NOTE>
