<FIRST>d f PM-OilPrices     01-07 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oil Prices,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Investors Remain Confident</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: For Saturday PMs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Concerns about OPEC's intentions over the next
six months remain evident in the oil futures market, but overall
investors remain confident.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the February contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil, rose
13 cents to close at $17.55 a barrel Friday. The contract recovered
on Thursday to post a gain of 34 cents after losing 28 cents on
Wednesday.
   Analysts noted that although investors have appeared optimistic
that the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries would stick
to its new six-month production agreement prices for contracts
between March and June showed only small gains of between 5 cents
and 6 cents a barrel.
   ``Although there has been a steady growth in confidence, prices
still favor the near-buy months,'' said Bob Baker, an analyst with
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc., ``so confidence erodes as the
months go out.''
   The 13-member cartel agreed late last year to cut back production
to 18.5 million barrels a day starting Jan. 1 from over 22 million
barrels a day. A worldwide oversupply of oil has kept crude prices
weak.
   Since the accord was announced, prices have risen from around the
$13 level.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange Friday, domestic
heating oil futures closed narrowly mixed. Analysts said cold
weather has not affected heating oil prices significantly because of
adequate supplies and forecasts of warmer weather.
   The February contract for home heating oil closed 0.13 cent
higher at 53.60 cents a gallon after rising 0.82 cent in Thursday's
session. Other contract months ended the day mixed.
   Gasoline futures followed crude oil, with the February contract
settling 0.32 cent higher at 47.72 cents a gallon. Other contract
months also ended mixed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
